commit_message:
Add API support for flavors

This patch adds the control API for flavors. The patch allows users to
create, delete, update and list flavors. This API is considered an
admin-only API, hence it's registered as part of the private endpoints.

DocImpact

Partially-Implements blueprint marconi-queue-flavors

Change-Id: Id29d29940f2ecabab0531edefe018c0dd2f39811

commit_message:
db API add show_nested to stack_get_all

Adds the option to get all stacks including nested stack, defaulted
to False.

blueprint: list-nested

[{'created': '2014-07-02 16:19:35.000000000', 'message': 'HyperV - Fix to implement hypervisor-uptime

The hyperv driver currently does not return the hypervisor-uptime.
This fix does the necessary changes to return the hypervisor-uptime
using the windows function GetTickCount64
More details about this function available at
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms724411%28v=vs.85%29.aspx

The function GetTickCount64 returns in millisecs the time since the host
is up. This fix converts the millisecs to Days/Hours/Mins/Secs using
datetime.timedelta.

Change-Id: Ib3cd90b17f64e369badaddb764ac9e6b9f6c1a4b
Closes-Bug: #1335559
'}, {'created': '2014-07-06 16:37:13.000000000', 'message': 'HyperV Driver - Fix to implement hypervisor-uptime

The hyperv driver currently does not return the hypervisor-uptime.
This fix does the necessary changes to return the hypervisor-uptime.
The uptime returned is in similar format to libvirt driver uptime

The uptime is based on the following:
1. Using the windows function GetTickCount64
More details about this function available at
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms724411%28v=vs.85%29.aspx

The function GetTickCount64 returns in millisecs the time since the host
is up.

2. Using WMI class Win32_PerfFormattedData_PerfOS_Processor
to check cpu load
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa394271(v=vs.85).aspx

3. Using WMI class Win32_LogonSession to check
the number of users logged in.
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa394189(v=vs.85).aspx

Change-Id: Ib3cd90b17f64e369badaddb764ac9e6b9f6c1a4b
Closes-Bug: #1335559

commit_message:
HyperV Driver - Fix to implement hypervisor-uptime

The hyperv driver currently does not return the hypervisor-uptime.
This fix does the necessary changes to return the hypervisor-uptime.
The uptime returned is in similar format to libvirt driver uptime

The uptime is calculated using the windows function GetTickCount64
More details about this function available at
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms724411%28v=vs.85%29.aspx

The function GetTickCount64 returns in millisecs the time since the host
is up.

Change-Id: Ib3cd90b17f64e369badaddb764ac9e6b9f6c1a4b
Closes-Bug: #1335559

[{'created': '2014-08-19 07:49:58.000000000', 'message': 'Remove wsgi and base controller dependency on token_api

The wsgi module and the base controller no longer depends on the
token_api, to interact with the token persistence system. The
token_provider_api.validate_token method and the KeystoneToken model
are now used.

This change is to ensure interactions with the token persistence system
are consistent and supporting the ability to toggle token persistence
in the future.

Change-Id: I5831d6a086241bc3a6691602e7527ae53c9411ce

commit_message:
Remove wsgi and base controller dependency on token_api

The wsgi module and the base controller no longer depends on the
token_api, to interact with the token persistence system. The
token_provider_api.validate_token method and the KeystoneToken model
are now used.

This change is to ensure interactions with the token persistence system
are consistent and supporting the ability to toggle token persistence
in the future.

Change-Id: I5831d6a086241bc3a6691602e7527ae53c9411ce
bp: non-persistent-tokens

commit_message:
Enhance GET /v3 to handle Accept header

Keystone wasn't handling the Accept header for GET /v3 according to
the HTTP 1.1 spec[1]. This change enhances the Keystone server so
that it supports using multiple values and qvalues in the Accept
header for GET /v3. This allows requesting a JSON Home or JSON
response with a preference for JSON Home, for example.

[1] http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616#section-14.1

bp json-home

Change-Id: Ifb204b6860c61a874ecbf92388878685ac437987

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

[{'created': '2014-08-13 17:48:11.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Remove _normalize_ip function

A floating IP fails to be assigned to an instance on
VMware, using VMwareVCDriver and nova-network.  The following
error is thrown: "NotImplementedError: Cannot load 'instance'
in the base class". The problem is caused by _normalize_ip,
which tries to assign an instance key to the FloatingIP object
that is needed by _translate_floating_ip_view. However, the
FloatingIP object does not have an instance field. Since
_translate_floating_ip_view just requires the instance UUID to
be assigned and returned as part of the result dict, the logic
to obtained the instance UUID is moved into
_translate_floating_ip_view, instead of assigning an instance key
to the FloatingIP object.

Change-Id: I2d7937e969bd87e53557842a22f3861f0d307b5e
Closes-Bug: #1356051

Closes-Bug: #1356051
'}, {'created': '2014-08-13 20:11:32.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Set default value for floating_ip['instance']

A list of existing floating IP (nova floating-ip-list) fails
on VMware, using VMwareVCDriver and nova-network.  The
following error is thrown: "NotImplementedError: Cannot load
'instance' in the base class". The problem is caused by
_normalize_ip, which tries to set an 'instance' field in
FloatingIP that is needed by _translate_floating_ip_view. The
instance is derived from the FixedIP that is assigned to the
'fixed_ip' field in FloatingIP. However, FixedIP may not have
an 'instance' field set, which can cause the NotImplementedError.
This can be fixed by returning a default empty dict when making
the get call.

Change-Id: I2d7937e969bd87e53557842a22f3861f0d307b5e
Closes-Bug: #1356051
'}, {'created': '2014-08-14 15:29:58.000000000', 'message': 'Fix NotImplementedError in floating-ip-list

A list of existing floating IP (nova floating-ip-list) fails
when using VMwareVCDriver/LibvirtDriver and nova-network.
The following error is thrown: "NotImplementedError: Cannot load
'instance' in the base class". The problem is caused by
_normalize_ip, which tries to set an 'instance' field in
FloatingIP that is needed by _translate_floating_ip_view. The
instance is derived from the FixedIP that is assigned to the
'fixed_ip' field in FloatingIP. However, FixedIP may not have
an 'instance' field set, which can cause the NotImplementedError.

The following patch removes _normalize_ip and assigns the
'instance_id' required by _translate_floating_ip_view to
the 'instance_uuid' in FixedIP, since only the instance ID

Closes-Bug: #1356051

commit_message:
Fix NotImplementedError in floating-ip-list

A list of existing floating IP (nova floating-ip-list) fails
when using VMwareVCDriver/LibvirtDriver and nova-network.
The following error is thrown: "NotImplementedError: Cannot load
'instance' in the base class". The problem is caused by
_normalize_ip, which tries to set an 'instance' field in
FloatingIP that is needed by _translate_floating_ip_view. The
instance is derived from the FixedIP that is assigned to the
'fixed_ip' field in FloatingIP. However, FixedIP may not have
an 'instance' field set, which can cause the NotImplementedError.

The following patch removes _normalize_ip and assigns the
'instance_id' required by _translate_floating_ip_view to
the 'instance_uuid' in FixedIP, since only the instance ID
is required and not the entire instance object.

Change-Id: I2d7937e969bd87e53557842a22f3861f0d307b5e
Closes-Bug: #1356051

commit_message:
Use checked commit when committing kazoo transactions

To avoid the case where the transaction appears to have
committed successfully (when it actually has not) create
a new checked_commit utility function and use it in the
zookeeper persistence backend to ensure that the transaction
has completed correctly (when it has not raise a new kazoo
exception that contains the failures to the caller, which can
then reraise that exception, examine the failures or do some
other action).

Change-Id: Ib169b36abb568a0e1516c4c786fccb30856661e1

I continue to believe that this really should be part of the QA mission, and as explained on the mailing list, believe that the rally team has generally not worked upstream when the features would be of greater benefit to OpenStack as a whole in other projects.

I don't see how making another over arching program actually helps OpenStack, and based on the fact that a bunch of things like statistics gathering outside of rally has to be duplicated again, I feel like OpenStack is demonstrably more fragmented if we greenlight this program in it's current state."}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-07-27 21:02:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sean, 

Thank you for reviewing proposal.
Could you please elaborate some of your points.  

1) What do you mean "the rally team has generally not worked upstream"? I mean:

  1) We are on stackforge
  2) Rally team contains more then 15 companies (in Juno)
  3) We added rally performance jobs to keystone, cinder, glance, neutron on every patch
  4) We are involving core teams of different projects in rally and helping them to start 
  5) We have own IRC chat where we are discussing everything


2) About statistics: 

There is no need to duplicate of any efforts here. Rally uses DB to store all results. Having single instance of DB will allow us to collect all statics. Results are in JSON, so parsing these results and using some basic aggregation script is one day of work, or even less.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-07-28 09:33:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-07-28 18:41:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Additionally, performance and scale is similar to the discussion we had for UX -- all projects should be tracking and improving these things."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-28 18:41:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Mark, 

Thank you for review. 
Let's compare scope of Rally and mission of QA program


QA mission:

    Develop, maintain, and initiate tools and plans to ensure the upstream
    stability and quality of OpenStack, and its release readiness at any
    point during the release cycle.


Rally scope is going to present OpenStack API for:

  1) run performance & verification tests (periodic or on demand) 
  2) profiling production clouds
  3) analyze performance & verification results (that will contain durations, profiling data, satori config discovering & logs)
  3.1) to detect  & debug issues (if something is failing we will have automatically collected profiles, logs, configs related to that, so it will take seconds not weeks to find & fix issues in production)
  3.2) track performance of different API calls (guarantee SLAs)
  3.3) track of performance of services in different API calls (be able to customize strategies, e.g. add more controllers/compute/volume nodes before users face perf issues) 

Nothing above is related to process of development of OpenStack.
And it doesn't fit to the QA program at all."}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-07-30 13:16:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-30 13:16:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"Nothing above is related to process of development of OpenStack. And it doesn't fit to the QA program at all."

I don't actually reach the same conclusion.  I actually agree that it would make a lot of sense for this to be a part of QA.

However, we have to remember that programs are primarily about teams.  If the teams doing the existing QA work and Rally are separate, then another program may make the most sense.

Of course, we could argue that for the mission of Rally (and QA) to be successful, we feel they must figure out how to work more closely.'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-07-30 21:08:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11938, 'date': '2014-07-30 21:15:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I do not agree that this is a QA project, and would very much like to see it integrated into OpenStack. 

I work on many production clouds and have used Rally for months now to generate performance data of deployed clouds, to help me determine whether or not configuration and hardware changes have caused any impact to performance. I think this tool offers a lot more daily value to OpenStack operators than to OpenStack developers.

By all means, integrate it into the QA toolchain too, but please do not block this valuable tool from being deployed as a part of every OpenStack cloud.'}, {'account_id': 10165, 'date': '2014-07-30 21:21:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add console interface to agent_ipmitool driver

The agent_ipmitool driver (ironic.drivers.agent.AgentAndIPMIToolDriver)
doesn't have a console interface. It should be using IPMITools'
IPMIShellinaboxConsole().

Change-Id: I780ff2df9ed1d673fa5f124efb73ca3ecd945c85
Closes-Bug: #1359466

Add __repr__ to KeystoneToken model

For better debugging/usability, add __repr__ to the KeystoneToken model.

commit_message:
Remove identity_api dependency on token_api

Remove the identity_api dependency on token_api. Now for each type
of event that would cause revocations (or delete of tokens) to occur
an internal callback notification is emitted and consumed by the
token_provider_api and the revoke_api (as appropriate). This required
a few new notification entity types ('user_password',
'user_removed_from_group'), but since these are not public notifications
the overhead should be minimal.

This change is to ensure interactions with the token persistence system
are consistent and supporting the ability to toggle token persistence
in the future.

Change-Id: I796f1b003a9d43b89940bb74d2c44d3cff215c72
bp: non-persistent-tokens

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-25 00:44:57.000000000', 'message': "Remove trust dependency on token_api

The trust_api and controllers no longer directly depend on the
token_api. The `validate_token` call on the `token_provider_api`
is now used to retrive token data.

The token_provider_api listens for trust deletion events to clean
up the token persistence backend. In support of this callback, it
is now possible to perform a .get_trust() and specifically request
deleted / expired / fully consumed trusts. This is done by passing
the kwarg 'deleted' with a value of 'True' to the `get_trust`
method.

This change is to ensure interactions with the token persistence
are consistent so that it is possible to support toggling
persistence of tokens.

Change-Id: Ifc7174d6473dfa279b3dc706a59bc58c812332b3
bp: non-persistent-tokens

commit_message:
Remove trust dependency on token_api

The trust_api and controllers no longer directly depend on the
token_api. The `validate_token` call on the `token_provider_api`
is now used to retrieve token data.

The token_provider_api listens for trust deletion events to clean
up the token persistence backend. In support of this callback, it
is now possible to perform a .get_trust() and specifically request
deleted / expired / fully consumed trusts. This is done by passing
the kwarg 'deleted' with a value of 'True' to the `get_trust`
method.

This change is to ensure interactions with the token persistence
are consistent so that it is possible to support toggling
persistence of tokens.

Change-Id: Ifc7174d6473dfa279b3dc706a59bc58c812332b3

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-12 03:18:52.000000000', 'message': 'Update AuthContextMiddleware to not use token_api

AuthContextMiddleware and the fall-through in the controller base
_build_policy_check_credentials now utilizes the KeystoneToken
model and uses token_provider_api instead of token_api.

In support of this change, the token auth plugin, the auth_context
builder, token bind check, and token controller have all been updated
to utilize the KeystoneToken model. Support for the federation data
has been added to the KeystoneToken model so that it can be used
in the auth context and associated code.

Associated tests that passed a raw token_ref to methods that now
expect the KeystoneToken model have been updated. This includes an
update to the revocation model to guard against users without domain
data (the federated user case).

Change-Id: I81da15137a0ab3778d835c8de1ec8ed9e5b301f6
bp: non-persistent-tokens

Associated tests that passed a raw token_ref to methods that now
expect the KeystoneToken model have been updated. This includes an

Change-Id: I81da15137a0ab3778d835c8de1ec8ed9e5b301f6

commit_message:
Update AuthContextMiddleware to not use token_api

AuthContextMiddleware and the fall-through in the controller base
_build_policy_check_credentials now utilizes the KeystoneToken
model and uses token_provider_api instead of token_api.

In support of this change, the token auth plugin, the auth_context
builder, token bind check, and token controller have all been updated
to utilize the KeystoneToken model. Support for the federation data
has been added to the KeystoneToken model so that it can be used
in the auth context and associated code.

Associated tests that passed a raw token_ref to methods that now
expect the KeystoneToken model have been updated. This includes an
update to the revocation model to guard against users without domain
data (the federated user case).

Change-Id: I81da15137a0ab3778d835c8de1ec8ed9e5b301f6
bp: non-persistent-tokens

commit_message:
Horizon changes for DVR

Feature completed :
1. Admin router panel
   + New "Distributed" column introduced.
   + New Field "Distributed" added on to
     router detail panel
2. Project router panel
   if logged in as "Admin"
   ======================
   + New distributed column introduced.
   + New Field distributed column added on to
     router detail panel.
   + New Router Field dropdown box introduced in
     create router form.
   if logged in as "nonAdmin"
   =========================
   + Router Type dropdown will be invisible for
     non admin.
   + Distributed information will be
     hidden from details panel.

implements: blueprint enhance-horizon-for-dvr

Co-Authored-By: Akihiro Motoki <motoki@da.jp.nec.com>

Change-Id: I995745dd72a8b750866c0977a7d7cf42036f716f

commit_message:
Raise HTTPNotFound error from V2 cert show API

There might be possibility of not having the CA file while
requesting certificate show API. API should raise HTTPNotFound
for clear error.
This patch raise this exception for V2 API. This has been fixed in
V3 API.

Adding UT also for the same.

Change-Id: Iafb33fce6433a31f9767067bbc45b95acd4ee511

commit_message:
auth_token cached token handling

auth_token handles tokens that are from its cache, uncached PKI
(compressed and ASN, "offline validation") and UUID/hashed tokens
("online" validation).

For all of these cases, the auth_token middleware was doing

1) expiration check
2) confirm token bind
3) store in cache

In some cases, some of these steps aren't necessary.

When getting the token from the cache
1) no expiration check is needed because the expiration time is
   stored as cache data and the token would be rejected during
   _cache_get.
2) Storing in the cache is unnecessary because the token is
   already in the cache.

When doing online validation, it's not necessary to do the
expiration check because the identity server would have rejected
the token if it was expired.

Closes-Bug: #1289075
Change-Id: I6afa98504215521538434f1f8a2d97585ce35de5

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V basic scenario volume partition name

On Hyper-V volumes are attached to SCSI passthrough devices that have a
progressive naming (sdb, sdc etc) and cannot match the requested name
(e.g. vdb).

Closes-bug: #1357925
Co-Authored-By: Adrian Bora <abora@cloudbasesolutions.com>
DocImpact
Change-Id: I429b07d2ed55e7875034bc10510a039f6042c724

commit_message:
Adds support for custom image formats in scenarios

Scenario Tempest tests don't work on Hyper-V due to the missing
support for VHD/VHDX image formats in the Tempest scenario comfiguration.

The commits adds options to specify custom image disk and container
formats, mantaining 'QCoW2' and 'bare' as the default options for
backwards compatibility.

Closes-bug: #1357691
Co-Authored-By: Ionut Balutoiu <ibalutoiu@cloudbasesolutions.com>
DocImpact

Change-Id: I41c09d5a682cdb068b97b4bd1be3403ee7973c7c

commit_message:
Hide the "Host Aggregates" admin panel if not enabled.

This checks ehther the extension is supported in nova and disables
access to the panel (hiding it) if not.

Closes-Bug: #1332066

Change-Id: Ibe35e0c46ac85e4e32b49453fa7fea0c3bb66548

[{'created': '2014-07-31 13:33:58.000000000', 'message': 'Use Alembic instead of Sqlalchemy-migrate in Manila

- Can emit ALTER statements to a database in order to change
  the structure of tables and other constructs
- Provides a system whereby "migration scripts" may be constructed;
  each script indicates a particular series of steps that can "upgrade"
  a target database to a new version, and optionally a series of steps
  that can "downgrade" similarly, doing the same steps in reverse.
- Allows the scripts to execute in some sequential manner.

1. Add Alembic migrations support.
2. Move 001_manila_init.py migration to
manila/db/sqlalchemy/alembic/versions/162a3e673105_manila_init.py.
3. Remove manila/db/sqlalchemy/migrate_repo directory.
4. Fix unit tests.
5. Add ability to runtime updrade/downgrade db.

Implements bp alembic-instead-of-sqlalchemy-migrate

commit_message:
Use Alembic instead of Sqlalchemy-migrate in Manila

Alembic offers the following functionality:
- Can emit ALTER statements to a database in order to change
  the structure of tables and other constructs
- Provides a system whereby "migration scripts" may be constructed;
  each script indicates a particular series of steps that can "upgrade"
  a target database to a new version, and optionally a series of steps
  that can "downgrade" similarly, doing the same steps in reverse.
- Allows the scripts to execute in some sequential manner.

1. Add Alembic migrations support.
2. Move 001_manila_init.py migration to
manila/db/sqlalchemy/alembic/versions/162a3e673105_manila_init.py.
3. Remove manila/db/sqlalchemy/migrate_repo directory.
4. Fix unit tests.
5. Add ability to runtime updrade/downgrade db.

Implements bp alembic-instead-of-sqlalchemy-migrate

Change-Id: Iadc0d9596e826323ba19bd25be741c401b90b688

Add an example how to change MTU via CLI.

to change MTU parameters.

commit_message:
Sync latest processutils from oslo-incubator

This sync is primarily being done to pull in commit
63c99a0f so that passwords are masked in exception and
error messages.

------------------------------------------------

oslo-incubator head:

commit 80a08a413fb0f23a056eca2d273b167f0a09bab6
Merge: 83c4098 d73f3b1
Author: Jenkins <jenkins@review.openstack.org>
Date:   Mon Aug 25 14:32:36 2014 +0000

    Merge "Remove unused/mutable default args"

-----------------------------------------------

The sync pulls in the following changes (newest to oldest):

63c99a0f - Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages
e184dd36 - Fix exception message in openstack.common.processutils.execute
d6b55fb2 - Remove `processutils` dependency on `log`

-----------------------------------------------

Change-Id: Ia92aab76fa83d01c5fbf6f9d31df2463fc26ba5c
Partial-bug: 1343604

commit_message:
Increase the default poll duration for Cisco n1kv

Increase the poll duration for Cisco N1Kv, from 10s to 60s and also
clean up the /etc/neutron/plugins/cisco/cisco_plugins.ini file. The
current poll duration of 10s causes that VSM to unnecessarily taking
frequent CPU cycles, resulting in the failure of other tasks in scale
configurations.

Closes-Bug: 1357030

Change-Id: I95747f35bae5b7157391c1698c0fe84d2126aa10

commit_message:
Validate cores and ram when booting instance

There is no validating for cores and ram in creating instance workflow.
The user can submit the form even the requested cores or ram are exceed
the quota.

Change-Id: I25d49f709d120a6a56692b174e17969cba1c8065
Closes-bug: 1349370

commit_message:
Enhance V3 extensions to provide JSON Home data

The V3 extensions are enhanced to provide JSON Home data for each
of the resources that they provide.

bp json-home

Change-Id: I6466cd583b22b260f8979717fa6ceafcbf252839

subject: Enhance V3 extension class to integrate JSON Home data

commit_message:
Enhance V3 extension class to integrate JSON Home data

The V3 extension class is enhanced to intercept JSON Home responses
and modify the response to include any JSON Home data that the
extension provides. Note that there is no JSON Home data provided
yet.

bp json-home

Change-Id: I940cef418b9a2f199ebd804b66dabe688f4845b8

subject: Change OS-INHERIT extension to provide JSON Home data

commit_message:
Change OS-INHERIT extension to provide JSON Home data

The V3 router class for the OS-INHERIT extension is changed to
provide JSON Home data for its resources.

bp json-home

Change-Id: I6023d7d8646c4ab5e5515fe5997fe8bd12a61a4e

commit_message:
Working on engine implementation: on_task_result()

* Implementing DefaultEngine.on_task_result()
* Unit tests
* Fixing ReverseWorkflowHandler
* Renaming 'task_result' to 'raw_result' in method signatures
* Other minor fixes and refactoring (etc. kwargs -> params)
* Backport of Python 2.7 method assertDictContainsSubset()

TODO:
* Take care of ad-hoc actions

Change-Id: Iab853124679be393237bfdaaffdc03e4b8f0d664

commit_message:
Raise Not Implemented error from V2 diagnostics API

In case any driver does not implement functionality of providing VM
diagnostics, HTTPNotImplemented error will be raised from driver.
Nova V2 API should catch the same and pass it with proper error message
for better debugging.

This patch catch & raise  HTTPNotImplemented exception for
V2 "os-server-diagnostics" API.

Adding UT also for the same.

Change-Id: I485d3487d01eba07e3c34f6ef9b5c707af54ebb7

commit_message:
Don't expose X-Auth-Token in heat CLI

Heat CLI exposes X-Auth-Token in debug mode. This patch replaces
X-Auth-Token's value with '{SHA1}<sha1oftoken>'. Some credentials
are exposed by keystoneclient as heatclient uses keystoneclient to
authenticate, it will be fixed in bug:100414.

Change-Id: Ic768af5a947535807ba449fb0aeb1eb98dac56e6
Partial-Bug: #1327019

subject: Adds a state metric to ceilometer
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-27 04:39:14.000000000', 'message': 'Adds a state metric to ceilometer

To allow accurate billing of VMs based on which state they are in,
this metric polls state on the pipeline interval, but also watches for
any instance events to ensure accurate state transition data.

A couple of new metrics were added (one for polling, and one for
notifications) that both return the same sample meter name. The
implementation is based on the way the instance metric currently
works.

Change-Id: I3c13d2ec149de93139482770bc56480a596731c2
'}]
commit_message:
Adds a state metric to ceilometer

To allow accurate billing of VMs based on which state they are in,
this metric polls state on the pipeline interval, but also watches for
any instance events to ensure accurate state transition data.

A couple of new metrics were added (one for polling, and one for
notifications) that both return the same sample meter name. The
implementation is based on the way the instance metric currently
works.

Change-Id: I3c13d2ec149de93139482770bc56480a596731c2

Thanks for fixing that.

My multi-node nova setup experience with devstack is small, I'm just trying to think this through.  You say that it's necessary to have this in mutli-node installs; thus if someone is doing the obvious thing of running a ./stack.sh with just n-cpu enabled; you're saying that it won't work unless they've also specified NOVA_VNC_ENABLED?

Because that sounds really confusing, especially as lots of people are starting to think about multi-node.  It feels like it would be best if we had something that worked more automatically in this case?

Am I mis-understanding?  Any ideas if we could auto-match some conditions to enable this?"}, {'account_id': 7175, 'date': '2014-07-17 14:17:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> thus if someone is doing the obvious thing of running a ./stack.sh with just n-cpu enabled; you're saying that it won't work unless they've also specified NOVA_VNC_ENABLED?

That is correct.  In order for horizon on a controller to be able to see VNC sessions and the like from separate controllers, those controllers need to have `vnc_enabled = True` in nova.conf as well as the proxying information present there (i.e., `vncserver_listen` and `vncserver_proxyclient_address` set).

The only way to do this currently is to enable n-novnc or n-xvnc on the compute node.  (In lib/nova, the only places vnc_enabled are set are both at ~line 505 and are currently dependent on the presence or lack of these services.)

To make this more concrete, local.confs for a compute node and a controller node can be found at http://paste.openstack.org/show/86945/ (these should work, but will not have VNC accessible through the dashboard).  Adding n-novnc to `$ENABLED_SERVICES` on the compute's local.conf will cause it to work, though it will now be running the extraneous service.  On the other hand, with my changes, if one adds `NOVA_VNC_ENABLE=True` to compute's local.conf, it will also work without enabling n-novnc.

Ideally, yes, we would check something more automatic for multi-node cases.  The only thing I can think of to check is `$MULTI_HOST`, and my worry there is that we would then set `vnc_enabled=True` and the like in too many cases.  Perhaps someone more familiar with the code could comment on this?"}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-07-18 01:13:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In that case, should we just turn this on by default for all compute nodes?  Or maybe, if required, invert the logic so you have to *disable* this if for some reason you don't want it?

Because it seems like in the most usual case, you always want it enabled, independent of running the proxies?"}, {'account_id': 7677, 'date': '2014-07-18 17:24:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The only downside is that it would cause launched qemu processes to listen for VNC connections.  If you weren't running the proxy, you'd have no way of connecting to these except by using a vnc client to connect directly.

Now, in a production deployment, if you weren't using VNC, you wouldn't want things listening for VNC connections for security reasons.  In a DevStack deployment, there's not really any downsides, though (unless you're weird and have compiled qemu to not have VNC support, and it barfs because of that)"}, {'account_id': 7677, 'date': '2014-07-18 17:24:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-07-22 14:26:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

The only way we are going to be able to set anything 'automatically' is to build a unified local.conf for multi-node that allows a compute node to peek into a controller node config to check for presence of either of the VNC proxies.

The MULTI_NODE var is poorly named and is not useful as a general indicator, it affects how nova-network is configured and may not necessarily be set in all setups.

The unified config is a long way off, if it is ever implemented, so the next least-bad solution is to add yet another config knob.  This default, to not change current behaviour, is correct."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-22 14:26:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
Add and document $NOVA_VNC_ENABLED for forcing VNC on

This allows multinode setups to function correctly without enabling the
unneeded n-novnc and n-xvnc services on pure compute nodes.

Change-Id: Ie02734bb598d27560cf5d674c9e1d9b8dca3801f
Closes-Bug: 1342155

If this is dependent on drivers, you might want to take the same approach for volume backups, where a configuration file is used to turn it on (until cinder exposes the ability to discover it)."}, {'account_id': 11880, 'date': '2014-07-14 21:41:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(9 comments)

Hi Lin Hua, I am not sure what exactly you mean, let me take a look and get back to you. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2014-07-14 21:47:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Cinder supports retyping of volumes.   If a specific driver doesn't have retype, cinder tries to do a volume migrate."}, {'account_id': 11880, 'date': '2014-07-15 00:12:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

cinder retype is only supported in cinder v2. It depends on the drivers (backend) that are tied with types. Types are set up through type-key extra spec. If cinder finds it can not retype, it will check if the migration policy is on-demand or never, if it is never, then cinder does not do anything, otherwise, it will do migration. By default in the horizon retype dialog UI, migration policy is never which is also the default in cinder cli command.'}, {'account_id': 11880, 'date': '2014-07-15 00:37:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-15 00:37:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

"}, {'created': '2014-07-15 00:37:36.000000000', 'message': "Enable changing volume type of a volume

Expose the functionality of the 'cinder retype' command in the UI.
It allows user to change the volume type of a volume whose status is
in-use or available when horizon's cinder API version is >= 2.

cinder retype is only supported in cinder v2. It depends on the
drivers (backends) that are associated with volume types. Volume types
are set up through type-key extra specs. During retype, if cinder
finds it can not retype, it will check if the migration policy is
one_demand or never. If the policy is never, then cinder does not do
anything, otherwise, it will do migration. By default, in the horizon
retype dialog UI, migration policy is never which is also the default
of the cinder cli command.

Implements: blueprint volume-retype
Change-Id: Id8bc539e1849f5910df34d7b76cc250ec82f9671
"}, {'created': '2014-07-15 02:22:54.000000000', 'message': "Enable changing volume type of a volume

are set up through type-key extra specs. During retype, if cinder

one_demand or never. If the policy is never, then cinder does not do

retype dialog UI, migration policy is never which is also the default
of the cinder cli command.

are set up through type-key extra specs. During retype, if cinder
finds it can not retype, it will check if the migration policy is
one_demand or never. If the policy is never, then cinder does not do
anything, otherwise, it will do migration. By default, in the horizon
retype dialog UI, migration policy is never which is also the default
of the cinder cli command.

Implements: blueprint volume-retype

commit_message:
Enable changing volume type of a volume

Expose the functionality of the 'cinder retype' command in the UI.
It allows user to change the volume type of a volume whose status is
in-use or available when horizon's cinder API version is >= 2.

cinder retype is only supported starting cinder v2.

If enabled_backends is specified in /etc/cinder/cinder.conf,
retype is actually performed by a specific driver.
It depends on the drivers (backends) that are associated
with volume types.
Volume types are set through type-key extra specs.

If enabled_backends in cinder.conf is not specified, volumes are
created by LVM so retype is actually performaned in LVM.

During retype, if cinder finds it can not retype, it will check
if the migration policy is on_demand or never. If the policy is
is never, then cinder does not do anything, otherwise, it will
perform migration. By default, in the horizon retype dialog UI,
migration policy is never which is also the default
of the cinder cli command.

Currently in horizon cinder api default version is 1. In order to
test this functionallity, you need to update
openstack_dashboard/local/local_settings.py to have the "volume"
API to use version 2 so the "Change Volume Type" action menu
shows up for the volume. If local_settings.py is not available, you
need to copy the local_settings.py.example file, change it to
local_settings.py, update other necessary settings and also update
have the API version setting like the followings:

OPENSTACK_API_VERSIONS = {
    #"data_processing": 1.1,
    #"identity": 3,
    "volume": 2
}

Implements: blueprint volume-retype

Change-Id: Id8bc539e1849f5910df34d7b76cc250ec82f9671

Refactor CreateRouter to use update_dict

At this point in time, 'distributed' is a positional argument and
thus doesn't need to be moved into the resource body.

commit_message:
Add hook scripts for the functional infra job

Infra jobs support hooks to customize behavior.  This change adds
scripts that are intended to be called by the neutron-dsvm-functional
jobs as hooks.   Defining hook behavior in-tree instead of directly in
the job definition has the advantage of allowing changes in hook
behavior to be tested before merge.

The gate_hook.sh script added by this change installs a rootwrap
filter to allow functional tests to destroy python processes that
they have spawned.  The tests use the python executable provided by
their tox env, and the default rootwrap configuration does not
support killing processes launched by non-system python executables.

This change will have to merge to master and stable/icehouse before
the supporting infra config change can be merged:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116458/

Partial-bug: #1360658
Change-Id: Idcc6195f91fac833c14892f27fb793048ef964b9

commit_message:
Add visibility filter to datastore versions

Allows datastore versions to be hidden from all users except those
explicitly allowed by their tenant. Implemented via a visibility
attribute for datastore versions (defaulting to 'public'), and a
datastore version member table for controlling access to non-public
datastore versions by tenant.

This commit provides the client functionality for integration tests
related to the datastore-visibility feature.

Implements: blueprint datastore-visibility
Docimpact: change to datastore version payload
Change-Id: Ic8024a631530ba295688d7e49e895f50cb2f32ef

commit_message:
Document how to add import exceptions

Add documentation for how to add import exceptions so hacking does not
complain about the way the library is used.

Change-Id: Ic33307215abbc38d3d3d2435588f79dc115510fd

commit_message:
Remove mention of Message objects from public docs

The Message class is not part of the public API of the library, so don't
refer to it in documentation that appears for the public API.

Change-Id: Ie28ce6f8f2c2de351c8a233b7de9dc31abaa9e04

commit_message:
Add Oracle ZFS Storage Appliance ISCSI Driver

ZFSSA ISCSI Driver is designed for ZFS Storage Appliance product
line (ZS3-2, ZS3-4, ZS3-ES, 7420 and 7320).
It uses REST API to communicate out of band with the storage controller
to perform the following:
* Create/Delete Volume
* Extend Volume
* Create/Delete Snapshot
* Create Volume from Snapshot
* Delete Volume Snapshot
* Attach/Detach Volume
* Get Volume Stats
* Clone Volume

Update cinder.conf.sample to include ZFS Storage Appliance
properties.

Certification test results:
	https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1356075

Change-Id: I2925c3e8cbe6f9d7a81ca70fcac7709714f07962
Implements: blueprint oracle-zfssa-cinder-driver

commit_message:
Bump up zake to be using the newer 0.1 or greater

0.1 brings in quite a few new hotness than prior
to it. The big one is multi-client -> single storage
which mimics many zookeeper clients attached to
the same zookeeper.

Change-Id: Iee6f4157743a094dd0d59dc12e66592594d54792

commit_message:
Clean up image build script

This change allows the image build script to support the existing
jobs that build images for distribution, as well as future jobs that
build the image within devstack for testing.

Change-Id: I6cae0ce336fde872678fafe6ba2b31af465944a1

I am still in favor of using network name instead of network uuid. 

For using port group network name will be much more descriptive in VC from the operator view. Though network name is allow duplicate in neutron, but it can be controller by creating port group logic.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-07-09 11:32:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi,
There is a problem with the name, that is, in neutron it does not need to be unique. We cannot change that as it is the way that the API works. As soon as you have two networks with the same name the solution breaks. It needs something uniqiue.

So my thinking is as follows:
1. In neutron when we create the DVS port group we create it with the following format:
    name-uuid
This enables the user to see the name of the port group and it enables the ID of the neutron network
I have tested this and it works.
It is also required for the VXLAN support
Thanks
Gary'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-07-09 11:33:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7148, 'date': '2014-07-09 13:31:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Use <name-uuid> looks can solve the problem for conflict. But considering vsphere does not allow network name to be unique for dvs pg and use same network name for same tenant would not be a good option. Why not considering creating networks with dup name, pop exception. 

We can discuss further tomorrow. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 10327, 'date': '2014-07-10 06:28:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think just using network name as the port group name is OK.It would be more straightforward and reasonable to use the network name.
We know neutron allows same network name among different networks, but vcenter does not allow it, and would prevent users from creating networks with same name from neutron side.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-07-10 08:22:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Feng, that will not work. This could be that the name is created on a different cluster on a different VC.
Once again it is not unique and will not work.'}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2014-07-10 09:21:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

"1. In neutron when we create the DVS port group we create it with the following format: name-uuid"

Gary,
If the network name format in VCenter side is "name-uuid", I feel we need to carefully identify the name string when we use a network in VCenter. For example, I use OpenStack to create network abc whose uuid is 123 first, and then create network 123 whose uuid is 456. There will be two network names, 'abc-123' and '123-456' in VCenter. I see the code in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/105352/ is attempting to use "if network_name in props.name" to identify the network name. Will that code regard 123-456 as the network abc created by OpenStack?'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-07-10 09:48:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Qin
The purpose of having the name was to have a human understandable text. So you are saying that someone is going to use a UUID for this name?
That just does not make sense. Do you know anyone who does that?
It just does not sound logical'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-07-10 09:56:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Feng,
We also should not be exposing vcenter details to Nova. Nova should work against the neutron API's and neutron names are not unique."}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2014-07-10 15:38:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Gary,
Maybe you feel my example is odd, but I do feel that is bug of the code, and can be avoid in a simple and straightforward way. I do not oppose to your network naming format. However, given that we have an exact network naming format, I think we can use a exact way to lookup the network.
Although a program can never become perfect, from a programmer's perspective, I still hope my program can become as good as possible. OpenStack code have many non-critical bugs that won't be fixed. If we do not fix this one now, I do think it will never be fixed. To me, it is better to kill those obvious bugs during code review, than to make our 'won't fix' bug backlog larger."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-07-11 06:53:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-11 06:53:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Network: add in a new network type - DVS

The support enables DVS network backends. In this case neutron
will return a vif type of DVS.

The name of the VC port group will be of the following format:
    <network-name>-<network-uuid>

The network name is so that the prefix will be easy for people to
understand. The UUID is to ensure that it will be unique.

Change-Id: Id125797632591bd799e215da7cbae07154e90344

commit_message:
fix network discovery meters

currently we let neutronclient authenticate against keystone. this
makes it impossible for us to figure out whether service is valid
until too late (when we call poll neutronclient).

this patch moves keystone validation to ceilometer's end so we can
check whether or not to poll neutron depending whether service is
registered or not. this makes it more inline with other polling
services.

Change-Id: If2768ad48b7e3f18af0c8111e15fc5243ec64f97
Closes-Bug: #1361818

commit_message:
Add Mellanox configurations and planning

1. Add Mellanox configuration in settings tab.
2. Create initial section for usign Mellanox hardware
   in the planning guide.

Partial-Bug: 1359216

Change-Id: I40de76cf61e7942850f34f16bb906d02a2a2761c
Signed-off-by: Aviram Bar-Haim <aviramb@mellanox.com>

commit_message:
Mark metadata_update RPC call deprecated

Log a deprecation warning if the metadata_update call is used,
in theory nothing uses this now, but it's possible folks could
try running the engine with a slightly older API version, or
have out-of-tree stuff using this RPC call (although I'm not
aware of any..), so maintain it for a transitional period (TBC,
maybe remove it after J2 has passed, or do we need to leave it
until K?)

Note the intention is to remove the metadata_update RPC call, but
maintain the metadata_update plugin interface (which is now only
used when it's necessary to do an internal refresh of the metadata
all external metadata update should happen via the resource_signal
interface, so it's compatible with the native API.)

Change-Id: Idf79389bc4250f91959cc13ae5fe7513aff6f291

commit_message:
Revert "Remove the temporary deploy element after rename"

This reverts commit ac73660c4091d43d2750d269076d756cb30d9ca9.

This was a backwards incompatible change - it broke the stable tripleo-heat-templates job.

Change-Id: Ideffca203db7b860b9f9d96c1d9f73e046519ec7

commit_message:
Update requirements.txt to include keystoneclient

Keystone client is required by nova client and needs to be in
requirements.txt. It is currently in test-requirements.txt but also
needs to be in install requirements.

Change Ief6cd7e752fd8c9e9157364f99e270da7faff074 introduced the
requirement for keystone client.

Change-Id: I91f58810e0511d0d4acc5bba0c0e946edf247896
Closes-Bug: 1358675

commit_message:
Should not send replies for cast messages

Cast messages will not contain a msg_id  and we're currently
sending messages to the default excahgne with empty msg_id.
In order to fix it we should not send replies if there is no
msg_id in message.

Change-Id: I5b1142029d2c718c3929cf6cf1f6e958b95a5c96
Closes-bug: #1355058

commit_message:
Back off initial migration to 34

Upgrading from the Havana release to Juno was failing because the
initial Juno migration didn't include a couple of migrations that
weren't in the initial Havana release but were added afterwards.

This change adds the 035 migration from Havana back in and moves
the initial Juno migration back to 034.

Change-Id: I012b3f707659557d1774bae78b1dd652bb1a4dd7
Closes-Bug: #1357498

commit_message:
Fix the conflict configuration on rabbitmq port

In current logic, rabbitmq port will be set to ssl-listening port,
this will make rabbitmq fail to start.
This submit will configure rabbitmq port for both ssl and non-ssl cases.

Closes-Bug: #1353884

Change-Id: I37dc9b656c553554b9bc636fe35c69744debe92a

commit_message:
Add a Cisco smoke test for testing plugins on actual Nexus switch

Fixes bug 1241262

This fix creates a Cisco smoke test for quickly testing Nexus plugin
operation (for both original Cisco Nexus plugin and the Cisco ML2
mechanism driver) operation on an actual Nexus switch.

The test requires SSH access to a Nexus switch which has
one ethernet interface available on which the user doesn't
mind VLANs being configured/unconfigured by the test.
In order to trigger the test to run, the user must provide
connection information for a Nexus switch (IP address,
username, password, and ethernet interface number).

The smoke test is based on existing Neutron unit tests.
If Nexus switch connection information is not provided,
the tests will default to being skipped.

Change-Id: I943fda97b4751b3687625121cda1ad9a82094337

commit_message:
Fix performance issues with brocade zone driver.

Removed firmware checks from common path as the ssh invoke_shell was taking 5 seconds to complete for each firmware check. Refactored to only do cfgsave in non-activate case. Removed extra calls to switch to get the active zoneset.

Closes-Bug: #1292119 (cherry-picked from commit: 371a58fd1d3fb1c2db7e1234f9c51f22b1b8787e) Change-Id: Ie1c2c0c603f6dd68439f2c2db74b21ea2dd0fc11

Change-Id: Ie0f1694517ca2ce3e1164a2eca8b933864a60045

commit_message:
Merged Fix performance issues with brocade zone driver.

Cherry-pick from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/97884/

Change-Id: I4ed108625416b42abd390e6aa227e97d4ebf8d7c

When i ran "./run_tests.sh -p zonemanager" command, i got a recommendation that the etc/cinder/cinder.conf.samples
file is not upto date. Hence i had run the " ./tools/config/generate_sample.sh" commnad. But it didn't update the file instead it deleted contents of the file. Hence i had restored the file in patch.

fc_zone_manager.py: Revereted the _build_driver method changes that are not required.
test_fc_zone_manager.py: Reverted the file to it's original state it had before this defect fix. As these changes are not required as per the orinal owner of the juno defect fix.

Change-Id: I4ed108625416b42abd390e6aa227e97d4ebf8d7c

commit_message:
Moved context creation to benchmark.engine

Before this patch, context was created in benchmark.runner
base. This patch moved context creation to benchmark.engine.

This change makes the architecture of Rally much cleaner.
e.g. runners don't know anything about benchmark context
(removing one dependency in code)

Another reason for this change is to work on phasing out
hardcoded "users" from required context objects. On the
benchmark.engine level, we have more information about
deployment (so we can choose to use this context or not
depending on what we are doing, e.g. loading with
pre-created users or without them)

Change-Id: I6d60e3563011840a13140ad345a819d2c0b8db1e

commit_message:
Refactored user creation code.

Moved user creation from /runners/base.py
to engine.py within the benchmark folder.
This will fix the duplication of users when trying
to use existing test users while running scenarios.

Change-Id: I7f55d4aab146cc28fd4940ee799b286f862a0164

'dogpile.cache.memcache'.

commit_message:
Change the sub-routers to provide JSON Home data

The sub-routers also need to provide JSON Home data for the
resources that they add.

bp json-home

Change-Id: Icbbd36a468d4fa7627ad7686f08fe98bbf3b51a4

subject: Change V3 router classes to provide JSON Home data

Change V3 router classes to provide JSON Home data

The V3 router classes are changed to provide JSON Home data for all
of their resources.

bp json-home

- gate-rally-dsvm-keystone http://logs.openstack.org/13/114813/10/check/gate-rally-dsvm-keystone/e16041f : SUCCESS in 21m 02s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 7514, 'date': '2014-08-26 14:26:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

The updated example looks good with one exception which is the timestamp.  The CADF timestamp needs to be a fully qualified ISO timestamp (aee spec. section 6.3.4) which has a format and also requires the timezone offset designator which is needed when the events are federated.  

Ideally, this should reflect the actual TZ in which the event was generated, but in cases where times are normalize to GMT you still need to indicate the TZ as being normalized.  

The spec provides the following instructions for unknown or normalized TZ: 

"•	If the time in UTC is known, but the offset to local time is unknown, the TZD SHALL be represented with an offset of "-00:00". This differs semantically from an offset "+00:00", which implies an actual UTC time zone designation." 


Other Examples (from the spec):

Example 2: "New York City, United States during Eastern Daylight Time (EDT) or UTC-04:00"
During the period when Eastern Daylight (saving) Time (EDT) is observed, the UTC offset for New York City would be UTC minus four hours or UTC-04:00. An example of a valid Timestamp typed value for New York City during EDT would be:
2012-03-22T13:00:00-04:00


Example 5: "Beijing, China; China Standard Time (CST) or UTC+08:00"
The UTC offset for Beijing, China, which does not observe daylight saving time, is UTC plus eight hours or UTC+08:00. An example of a valid Timestamp typed value for Beijing would be:
2012-06-28T08:00:00+08:00'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-08-26 14:54:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 7514, 'date': '2014-08-26 15:03:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1

The timestamp looks good now.  Just need to see if we can ever actually get a real TZ in OpenStack (a reliable clock likely governed by Keystone).'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2014-08-26 15:30:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:26:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:27:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:34:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified+1

commit_message:
Make BaseValidationTestCase

Other parts of the Keystone API will need to extend this, so naming it
Base makes more sense. Also adding module level variables for valid and
invalide enabled types as well as creating a update schema validator
object that can be extended in subsequent validation test patches.

Change-Id: I2ffaa784d2bf1e0d785fa1b371b404b4dfd0ac13
bp: api-validation

commit_message:
labs: add snapshot_cycle command

This changeset adds the new command, snapshot_cycle. It can be used to
replace four lines that often go together. The command handles a full
cycle needed for a snapshot: queueing shutdown.sh, booting the VM,
waiting for it to shutdown, and taking a snapshot.

Change-Id: I13276088bd44326f475bf7477ad2ed27db2dbbe9

(9 comments)

I'm not sure about adding the comments to our template. I think the reason we haven't added them until now is that they should be in the attributes file where the sysadmin actually change them. If you change them in the config file, then they will be overwritten by chef. Keeping them in the config file was also deemed to be clutter. I can't remember where this was discussed though :/

Also, even when keeping the comments, I don't think it makes sense to keep the default values commented out. Those defaults should be stored in the attributes file.

Anyway, I don't feel too strongly about this. The -1 is for the inline nits and mostly the TODO items there which should go away."}, {'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2014-08-05 15:14:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(9 comments)

Ionut, addressed your template comments.

As for comments in the templates, I really like having them there to be able to look at a node and get a better idea of how it was converged.   Having the defaults in there also helps with analysis, but I agree we should do a better job of putting more comments in the attribute/defaults files across all the cookbooks.    A final reason for doing it this way is that for me, it's easier to do base release to cookbook diffs to see what has changed."}, {'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2014-08-05 15:15:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-05 15:15:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Update keystone conf files for Juno

* Update paste.ini
* Update keystone.conf
  - Add in description comments
  - Add project_ for deprecated ldap tenant_
  - Remove unused user and group _domain_id_attributes
* Update specs as needed

Change-Id: Ifbd5fac220fff7723b3de349ca57cd96a4b6910a
Closes-bug: #1351459

commit_message:
labs: add option for VM gui type

This changeset adds an environment variable and an option that can be
used to change the type of VirtualBox VM GUI used while building the
nodes.

Valid values are gui (default), sdl (minimal gui), and headless.

The resulting node VMs can then be started with or without GUI as
before.

Change-Id: If12f4ba6dc455972b6332318ed1261e2c9de8c3f

commit_message:
labs: add export via clone VM directory

This changeset introduces a new export method: exporting the named node
VMs as clones to the img directory.

The -e option takes now an argument (ova or dir) to distinguish between
exporting to an OVA package file and exporting to the img directory.

Unlike the OVA package files, this method preserves snapshots.

The resulting vbox files can be imported as VMs via VirtualBox GUI
(Machine->Add).

Change-Id: I7a8801de4b69796f3291a9e3a5896a055859121f

commit_message:
labs: allow node selection

Osbash only accepts commands for the cluster or a single node. With this
patch, any set of nodes can be passed as arguments to osbash.sh.

Change-Id: I8d178268f683ad70dbf275b75582acb05e7577ca

Update OS-EP-FILTER API

Update the API doc for the Keystone extension OS-EP-FILTER with the
new Endpoint Grouping APIs.

Related spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/102023/

Change-Id: If69f9d5c74ebf185f62974ad2d1da26778c6f15b

hanging out in shell.py. However, I think some of the interfaces are a
little strange.

For example, to update some metadata on an account, we do this:

    opts = {'meta': ['thingone:val1', 'thingtwo:val2'],
            # et cetera
           }
    with SwiftService(opts) as swift:
        swift.post()

That seems odd, and it makes it difficult to do things like, say,
update different metadata on two different containers (you need to
build two SwiftService objects instead of reusing one). I think I'd
rather have the metadata and its associates be passed as params to
post() instead of passed into the constructor.

That's not a hard requirement from me, though. I could probably be
convinced otherwise if you'd like to argue the point.

All the reader methods (stat, list, download, etc.) look good, though."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-07-08 21:18:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

I mean, I guess the post and upload methods do take an optional options dictionary... maybe what I'm after is for that to be mandatory.

Also, do you have any thoughts on including per-object metadata in upload()? Right now, every object winds up with the same metadata on it. Yes, one can make many calls to upload(), but then one loses the parallel uploads."}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-07-08 21:20:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

> For example, to update some metadata on an account, we do > this:

> opts = {'meta': ['thingone:val1', 'thingtwo:val2'], # et cetera}
>
> with SwiftService(opts) as swift:
>     swift.post()

I don't think this is necessary because the options for each call can be overridden for each operation.

In this case I'd expect the swift service to be created with a default set of options, and the calls to post have a custom set of options.

opts1 = {'meta': ['thingone:val1', 'thingtwo:val2'], # et cetera}
opts2 = {'meta': ['thingone:val11', 'thingtwo:val22'], # et cetera}

with SwiftService() as swift:
    swift.post(container="container1", options=opts1)
    swift.post(container="container2", options=opts2)

It is certainly possible that this interface could be cleaned up to explicitly take arguments for the things we want to override.'}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-07-08 21:23:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

Looks like we crossed over there.

I see your point about the options, and about the object metadata on uploads. Even though there's nothing stopping you from making lots of calls to upload and joining the iterators later, that's certainly not ideal.

I need to look at the awkward upload specification anyway, so I'll combine those two together and try to come up with something better."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-07-08 21:55:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

Oh, I didn't even notice that about the uploads returning iterators so they're chainable. Maybe stick that in the docstring? That'd certainly be nice for folks to know; if they're spreading objects across multiple containers, knowing that they can do that concurrently would be nice."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-08 22:05:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Verified-1

Ok, I have taken the previous comments and modified the interfaces for upload, stat and post.

stat() can now operate on a list of objects.

post() has been similarly updated with the opportunity to override the options on a per-object, and per-call basis.

The awkward tuple interface of upload() has been tweaked so that the object list is always a 3-tuple containing a source, destination and options dict per object upload.

Each call also now has a much more useful docstring detailing the inputs, potential return values and potential errors raised and well as some more in depth usage explanation where required.

Hopefully this will be a more appealing API than it was previously. The changes will mean I really need to do some thorough testing on my side, but I wanted to get the API out for comments asap.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-13 22:41:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Verified-1

Now that I've got a build verified by jenkins again, I thought it was worth reposting this comment:

I have taken the suggestions and observations made in the previous comments and modified the interfaces for upload, stat and post.

stat() can now operate on a list of objects.

post() has been similarly updated with the opportunity to override the metadata and headers on a per-object, and per-call basis.

The awkward tuple interface of upload() has been tweaked so that the object list is always a 3-tuple containing a source, destination and options dict per object upload. The options supplied to each object are now used to determine whether a None input is uploaded as an empty object or a dir marker.

Each call also now has a detailed docstring describing the inputs, valid options, potential return values and potential errors raised and well as some more in depth usage explanation where required.

Hopefully this will be a more appealing API than it was previously."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-19 19:46:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: -Verified

What is this new futures dependency anyway?  I didn't really see it called out in the commit - might be good to have something there for packagers or whaterver?"}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:56:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

(1 comment)

I've not seen any issues importing/using the futures package in any of my virtualenvs on any of my systems.

The futures library is a high level library for asynchronously executing tasks on a thread pool. It's a new feature added to core Python 3.2 and backported to 2.6+ with the futures package. It's also been separately added to global-requirements.txt in the openstack/requirements repository for icehouse, so if there was a problem as fundamental as this I'm sure someone else would have hit it by now.

Really sorry I couldn't be more helpful!"}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:28:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

Span up a fresh precise vm to test the futures problem, but I can't recreate the issue there either."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2014-08-21 23:04:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27: Code-Review+1

(3 comments)

Hey Joel, this is great!

FWIW, I wouldn't mind at all if you wanna just slurp the doc fixes from my dependent change into this one.

I have an outstanding question for notmyname regarding what if anything needs to happen to manage adding the new depends.  Even if he doesn't say it's necessary; I think it's reasonable to add a note to the commit message.

Regarding some comments I made; some of the new service methods signatures that take lists of tuples sorta scare me (currently swiftclient has a lot of apis where inputs/ouputs to it's functions/methods are tuples and it's sort of PITA) - but I'm probably just jaded and I think there's already been some bike-shedding there; so I may be a little late to the party to complain.  But these API's seem to have a way of haunting us.

I guess I sort of imagined a struct like class that duck types to a string but can have some optional attributes hung on it and then the service class api's could do things like:

    service.post('mycontainer', ['myobject'], options=myoptions)

or

    service.post('mycontainer', [SwiftObject('myobject', options=myoptions)])

instead of:

    service.post('mycontainer', [('myobject', None), options=myoptions]

or

    service.post('mycontainer', [('myobject', myoptions)])

I particularly think I'd like something like this for the object upload api, where the trivial case might just:

    service.upload('mycontainer', os.listdir('/stuff/to/put/in/container'))

But on the sneaky you might:

    service.upload('mycontainer', [SwiftObject('/path/to/file', object_name='foo')])

... dunno; if this lands as is, there's always the *chance* we might be able to get in something that might be more maintainable long term before the API get's widely adopted and we're too scared to change it."}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-08-22 15:09:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

I see your point about fixed size tuples, so I'll have a go at coming up with a new version along the lines of your suggestion. It will probably need two new classes 'SwiftUploadObject' and 'SwiftPostObject', and I'd imagine there might need to be some trickery to cope with directory markers in the case of:

    swift.upload(container, listdir(directory))

Let me have a play and see what I can come up with. Luckily I'm not using this code in too many other places yet :)"}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-08-22 15:42:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

(3 comments)

I think I've addressed all the comments. New code drop later."}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-08-23 11:49:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 28.'}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-08-23 11:52:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 28:

There were only positive responses to the class based uploader/post operations that allow us to upload/post using just file/object name strings in the basic case, and I think it's better so here's the new version of the patch.

This also includes all the documentation updates from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116120/ and is rebased onto the latest master."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-23 12:47:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add importable SwiftService incorporating shell.py logic

This patch adds a SwiftService class that incorporates the high
level logic from swiftclient/shell.py. It also ports shell.py to
use the new class, and updates the code in swiftclient/multithreading.py
to allow the SwiftService to be used for multiple operations whilst
using only one thread pool.

Currently, code that imports swiftclient has to have its own logic for
things like creating large objects, parallel uploads, and parallel
downloads. This patch adds a SwiftService class that makes that
functionality available in Python code as well as through the shell.

Change-Id: I08c5796b4c01001d79fd571651c3017c16462ffd

commit_message:
labs: make export a separate operation

Export is currently only possible at the end of a node rebuild.

With this patch, export becomes a separate operation that can be
executed at any time without changing the cluster.

Change-Id: I3e0780ef7264577a0c90e53bb7bf6f7079de88ec

commit_message:
Renewing ATC exceptions for Horizon

Jaromir and Liz have continued to provide significant UX input and
design for features being contributed to Horizon. Several features
reflect their contributions. The project would suffer without their
ongoing contribution and I would like their efforts to be formally
recognized.

Change-Id: I63884702da5ccc02d3ee0b0a0a2d9c35a13e3a70

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/49/111149/5/check/noop/7661b6f : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-08-14 21:37:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

@Russell, Jay,

What would it mean to accept a program, but not incubate any of the projects in it?

------------

I think that a shared-filesystem program makes sense, and am +1 on adding that functionality to OpenStack. I have spoken to the proposed PTL regarding the overlap (or lack thereof) with Cinder, and was satisfied with the answers (also summarized on the graduation wiki page).

However, I am slightly concerned that it appears there is really only one company behind Manila at this point, and there's not much of a developer community.

http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=all&module=manila&release=juno&metric=commits

None of the SUSE or B1 commits appear to be functional changes (they are mostly oslo related cleanup).

http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=all&module=manila&release=juno&metric=commits&company=suse

http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=all&module=manila&release=juno&metric=commits&company=b1%20systems


Even within the major contributing company, there are only four active contributors this cycle, accounting for 77% of their code contributions, and 67% of the overall code written for Manila this cycle.

http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=all&module=manila&release=juno&metric=loc&company=mirantis
http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=all&module=manila&release=juno&metric=loc


----------------------

I am placing a -1 vote here because I don't think it makes sense in this case to create a program but not accept the only project it would contain."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-18 13:15:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Deva: It's generally fine to have a program without an incubated project -- we bless the team as essential to the production of OpenStack and the achievement of our long-term goals, but do not feel that the project is ready to incubate yet."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-18 13:15:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-18 13:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/49/111149/5/check/noop/aebbc42 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-18 13:24:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Regarding the diversity comment: I'm more concerned about the number of developers than the diversity in company representation. We established that coming from a single company is not a barrier to incubation (it's a barrier to integration). But projects that are too small are at greater risk of being abandoned -- which raises the question of our capability to include "small" projects.

In that case the contribution profile looks a lot like Designate's, so i wouldn't hold it against Manila. If we think (1) shared filesystems are a nice feature, (2) it's simpler to have it as a standalone project than as a cinder extension, and (3) the architecture and code are solid, then I think it's fine to approve for incubation.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:10:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:10:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:10:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:11:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:15:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:20:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Does manila currently have a viable open source driver that has an HA story? If not what is the plan for one?'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-08-19 20:40:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Besides my reservations about expanding the scope of OpenStack while many folks (including myself) think our development model is hitting some fundamental growing pains that we have yet to address. I am concerned that there is no detailed roadmap to fix or even an acknowledgement in the wiki of the issues raised by the TC. Issues that ttx listed out:

1. The Cinder relationship (code was originally copied as a template, but now evolved on its own, common code is being osloified, Manila can pull architectural improvements directly from Nova)
2. Community size/width with most commits coming from same person(s) and same company
3. The driver/vendor aspect (avoid another Neutron with no first-party driver really viable, getting swamped by driver requests, relationship with glusterfs)
4. User interest (is it something people want)'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-20 07:27:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

I think Manila needs incubation to reach the next step.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-08-20 20:36:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I'm still thinking about Jay's mailing list posts asserting that programs actually discourage innovation."}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2014-08-21 14:55:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I read Jay Pipes' ML messages and I think his concerns are important and the TC should find a way to make sure that it's not unintentionally squashing competition.

Manila is not Ceilometer however and I don't see how the concerns raised relate to this request.

The current governance process seems to require that projects become incubated under a program. I don't have a problem with changes to the governance process, but I think this request has to be considered under the existing process, not the process that people wish existed.

What is the alternative? Block this request until the TC resolves its stance on programs? Incubate the project under some other existing program?"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-08-21 15:01:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Ben,

Note that I was not comparing Manila to Ceilometer or any other OpenStack project on the ML :) I have just been expressing my thoughts on whether the current rigid structure we've put in place regarding Programs and governance is serving our users best.

Cheers,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-22 09:22:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I agree, whether or not you like the concept of programs should not influence the vote here. If you agree with Manila being incubated, you should agree to the addition of a program. Killing programs is a separate topic :)'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-08-26 16:01:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

Yep agreed, and now that I was able to write about my thoughts on the mailing list, I'm comfortable voting +1. http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/044086.html"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-08-26 19:52:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:34:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Allow providing a default value to CLI loading

Allow users to specify a default value to loading auth plugins from the
CLI so that you can fallback to some default behaviour if the user
doesn't specify a plugin.

Change-Id: I44eb838f7ccc3b377dd1ba53dbb941e973e4a22e

commit_message:
Remove devstack/devstack-gate from projects

Repo devstack-gate has a requirements file but no setup.py, so we cannot
gate for changes there. Remove it from the list so that a broken
file will not break the requirements post job.
Similar for devstack.

Change-Id: I19049439e497f549313fe162ded2f696f679ec8c

commit_message:
Add mysql devel as testonly alongside mysql-server

Neutron needs to be able to install MySQL-python in the functional
test job, which requires devstack to install mysql devel libraries as
testonly.

As per sdague's recommendation mysql devel libraries are now installed
for nova as well.  In the future, any service that installs
mysql-server should also install mysql devel libraries for consistency.

Related-bug: #1346444

Change-Id: Ie715841e33a2c2d31cb4ac724b302eb98ed3366a

commit_message:
Use empty list in list_join for validation

Calling list_join on the list of ResourceGroup's attributes in a
SoftwareConfig fails during template validation with:

ERROR: Property error : my_config: config "list_join" must operate on a
list

Closes-Bug: 1358831
Change-Id: I39d2da7a28ba53fbe3a95bff0198fa5c2f87aa3b

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-07 09:36:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add parameter to customize Qpid receiver capacity

In Qpid rpc backend, receiver capacity is 1 and is hardcoding.
User can not customize it. This patch adds a parameter to make
user can specify receiver capacity in conf file.

- Reference about Receiver Capacity(Prefetch) from Qpid Doc
By default, receiver requests the next message from the server
in response to each fetch call, resulting in messages being
sent to the receiver one at a time. As in the case of sending,
it is often desirable to avoid this roundtrip for each message.
This can be achieved by allowing the receiver to prefetch messages
in anticipation of fetch calls being made. The receiver needs to
be able to store these prefetched messages, the number it can hold
is controlled by the receivers capacity.

Change-Id: I966b512aba6bdd8e9c5cf65cae01bfd21f04f330
Closes-Bug: #1353914
'}, {'created': '2014-08-13 03:43:18.000000000', 'message': 'Add parameter to customize Qpid receiver capacity
