commit_message:
Add parameter to customize Qpid receiver capacity

In Qpid rpc backend, receiver capacity is 1 and is hardcoding.
User can not customize it. This patch adds a parameter to make
user can specify receiver capacity in conf file.

- Reference about Receiver Capacity(Prefetch) from Qpid Doc
By default, receiver requests the next message from the server
in response to each fetch call, resulting in messages being
sent to the receiver one at a time. As in the case of sending,
it is often desirable to avoid this roundtrip for each message.
This can be achieved by allowing the receiver to prefetch messages
in anticipation of fetch calls being made. The receiver needs to
be able to store these prefetched messages, the number it can hold
is controlled by the receivers capacity.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I966b512aba6bdd8e9c5cf65cae01bfd21f04f330
Closes-Bug: #1353914

commit_message:
VPNaaS: Enable UT cases with newer oslo.messaging

Now that 1.4.0.0a3 of oslo.messaging has been added to Neutron
requirements, the unit test cases in VPNaaS code can be
uncommented and included in the tests. These tests ensure that
the correct validator is called, when validation is performed.
This adds similar tests to the reference and Cisco VPNaaS
implementation.

Change-Id: I62e3f8f3ec5fcceccd13891b1aa142869e1d88a1
Closes-Bug: 1349829

[{'created': '2014-01-15 16:42:55.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: VM diagnostics (v3 API only)

There is no formal definition for the VM diagnostics. For the
V2 API the diagnostics will be returned as they are today.

For the V3 api the diagnostics will have the format defined at:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Nova_VM_Diagnostics

This will support backward compatibility with the existing API's.

Part of the blueprint v3-diagnostics

DocImpact

Change-Id: I4128e76622e73a40d25fb50b10b1c1ac710a5cc4

commit_message:
libvirt: VM diagnostics (v3 API only)

There is no formal definition for the VM diagnostics. For the
V2 API the diagnostics will be returned as they are today.

This will support backward compatibility with the existing API's.

Part of the blueprint v3-diagnostics

DocImpact

Change-Id: I4128e76622e73a40d25fb50b10b1c1ac710a5cc4

commit_message:
Add template attr. for subnet, router create in Nuage plugin

subnet create and router create commands now gives the ability
to the user to create subnets and routers via neutron cli with
additional attributes nuage_subnet_template and nuage_router_template
respectively. The instantiated subnet and router inherits the properties
of the template that was mentioned in the additional parameters.

Change-Id: Ib73313e840cb35ede89df858baa536aab883efa2
Closes-Bug: #1353112

commit_message:
5.1 Release Notes

Copied release-notes/v5-0 to v5.1

Has been marked for Beta in release table
050-known-issues includes link to LaunchPad for all issues;
  the list is not ready for Beta

Deleted 019-new-features and 039-resolved-issues from v5-1 directory
(they were added especially for 5.0.1)

Added v5-1-icehouse-full.rst

v5-1/020-new-features contains list of new features

v5-1/030-other-enhancements contains additional improvements and a linke
to the 5.1 blueprint summary page.

v5-1/040-resolved-issues now includes items for 5.0.1 known issues
that have been fixed in 5.1

v5-1/050-known-issues now includes 5.0.1 known issues that have not
been fixed for 5.1

Change-Id: Id825efaced949a9e264ab20f18b9a837e1452c70

commit_message:
Add the ability to benchmark across multiple queues

Previously, all operations where performed on a single queue. This patch
introduces the ability to distribute operations across multiple queues,
which is important to measure since we know that the mongod driver has
some per-queue performance limits, but that it has several features
which allow for scaling load by spreading it across multiple queues.

Note that the default of 4 queues was chosen somewhat arbitrarily, and
may be adjusted later as we gather more data.

As part of this patch, queue classes and sample messages were hoisted
so they can be shared across all greenlets. Sharing a requests
session across all workers should improve the performance of the
benchmarking tool itself.

Change-Id: Iac6625b0214d40156da1c2bebe738fa453f184d1

commit_message:
Fix divide by zero bug in benchmark workers

This change checks for a zero denominator before attempting the
relevant calculations, otherwise allowing the statistic to
default to zero.

Change-Id: I3d21652e447430eccac4723348eea5f58384accd

commit_message:
Make use of openvswitch elements

Neutron and network-utils elements now depends of the new
openvswitch elements and delegate all openvswitch installation
and configuration into the openvswitch elements.

Closes-Bug: #1316985
Change-Id: Ib5c18e85317e6120b420d21790c26c21f4bbb0e4

Add _store_ip_allocation method

This refactor supports patch [1]
The code to store the IPAllocation is moved to a specific
method _store_ip_allocation

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100963

commit_message:
Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages

When a ProcessExecutionError is thrown by processutils.execute(), the
exception may contain information such as password. Upstream
applications that just log the message (as several appear to do) could
inadvertently expose these passwords to a user with read access to the
log files. It is therefore considered prudent to invoke
strutils.mask_password() on the command, stdout and stderr in the
exception.

Cherry-pick from review.openstack.org/109417
Cherry-pick from review.openstack.org/116763
Partial-Bug: #1343604

Change-Id: I5902391e244a2cb6012a0fafa2dd58e8830e80e3

commit_message:
Make strutils.mask_password more secure

Make some enhancements to strutils.mask_password to allow it to catch
more cases of passwords in strings. Test cases have been added to test
for these newly added situations.

The following is a listing of patterns that will be handled. The
keyword that mask_password uses (a list of four now) is represented by
<key> and the password is shown as <password>. Quotes (both single and
double) are represented as <quote>.

--<key> <password>
--<key> <quote><password><quote>
<key> = <password>
<key> = <quote><password><quote>

All existing tests and patterns are still handled.

Cherry-pick from review.openstack.org/113407
Partial-Bug: #1345233

Change-Id: If8a08c5248dec4e5d0860cce9e8d2266f7d49e38

commit_message:
Fix legacy tests using system policy.json file

Steps to reproduce:

1. Create a new file named '/etc/glance/policy.json' and inside it
paste:

    {"context_is_admin":  "role:admin"}

2. Run tests. Some of the tests under glance.tests.integration
.legacy_functional.test_v1_api will fail with errors such as
'MismatchError: 403 != 201'. These tests will pass without policy.json
in place.

The outcome of the tests should be isolated from the surrounding
environment, so this patch copies policy.json from glance's data files
(glance/tests/etc/policy.json) into the tests directory to avoid this
problem.

Change-Id: I27903ee4ebb7bad243c4f1b2d01096bfb93f1008
Closes-Bug: 1184056

commit_message:
Change autogenerate to be unconditional

Template for generating db migration scripts are now not run according
to used plugins. Target environment is set to use all available models
but also used plugins are kept for backward compatibility.

Part of this patch is script that will drop unused tables to avoid
generating the drop in future migration scripts.

Change-Id: I90a7d3416de24f2317ccdeb828bb8bd973ee5e61
Closes-bug: #1346638

commit_message:
Avoid refreshing PCI devices on instance.save()

Currently the way we refresh Instance.pci_devices causes current-version
PciDevice and PciDeviceList objects to be sent back to a potentially old
client. This is because remotable methods don't undergo backporting
obligatorily in the way that remotable_classmethod ones do. This is
currently a problem for pci_devices and security_groups, although it is
handled differently for things like info_cache so that it's not a
problem.

The resolution to this is rather complicated, so this patch just avoids
the implicit update (which is probably never used and actually generating
some more DB traffic) for the time being.

Change-Id: I33e584c42c9484912ccc3d38b67a6a7ee3d69a10

commit_message:
Fix Python 3 testing

Raising SkipTest at import time fails in recent version of the test
suite. We change that by being more picky at one should or should not be
tested based on what we managed to import; the upside is that we test a
few more things under Python 3 now.

Change-Id: I8971c7291cb261faf00fec73cf53b6132bdaf948

I don't understand this. Keystone doesn't support revoking by audit_chain_id. If you revoke a token, the revocation event should use the audit_id and the scope. Then when matching a token against the event, it should check the token's audit id and audit chain id against the event audit id and the scope against the scope."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-08-20 22:59:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I think the "require the scope" bit is wrong from an audit_id perspective. the reason to use the scope with expires_at (which is kept for non-audit_id tokens) is for preventing bleed across unrelated tokens.

The audit_chain_id revocations are not in place, but are supported in code. Revoking a single token and having the entire chain revoked (every time) breaks horizon and other clients (it makes revocation events a non-starter from a compatibility standpoint). I was expecting to add cases and/or support to the REST api once we moved to audit_ids for revoking the chain not just the individual token.

I'll discuss this with you further on IRC, but in short whole chain revocations on any revocation just serves to break things at this point. we should require specific scenarios to revoke the whole chain.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-08-20 23:00:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Instead of using the expiry of the token which can collide (is non
unique in some/many cases) use the new Audit ID for the tokens when
revoking a single token via the token revocation events.

Support for revoking by the audit_chain_id has been added to the
token provider, however, the REST API has not been updated to
accept an argument to revoke the chain. Support for revoking
the entire chain is in place to allow Keystone to internally
revoke an entire chain in certain circumstances. Exposing the
ability to revoke the entire chain via the REST API may occur
based upon further design discussions.

commit_message:
Revoke by Audit Id / Audit Id Chain instead of expires

Instead of using the expiry of the token which can collide (is non
unique in some/many cases) use the new Audit ID for the tokens when
revoking a single token via the token revocation events.

Support for revoking by the audit_chain_id has been added to the
token provider, however, the REST API has not been updated to
accept an argument to revoke the chain. Support for revoking
the entire chain is in place to allow Keystone to internally
revoke an entire chain in certain circumstances. Exposing the
ability to revoke the entire chain via the REST API may occur
based upon further design discussions.

Change-Id: I840355ccd9bcfcd88aa139184731c056808c2c8f
bp: non-persistent-tokens
Closes-Bug: 1292283

commit_message:
Share unittest between v2 and v2.1 for hide_server_addresses extension

This patch make the v2.1 hide_server_addresses extension running on v2
unittest, also delete the v3 unittest.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I9b8e8d10ba59b344d5bdf285fffffd98ed02ebc0

commit_message:
bump pycadf to 0.6.0

v0.6.0 introduces support for a federated credential model, which is
required for keystone to emit audit notifications during federated
authentication in bp audit-support-for-federation

Change-Id: I6c07adf3c06398441a8c38be656c682687a9eb2f

[{'created': '2014-08-26 00:36:39.000000000', 'message': "Add flake8 2.2.3

Flake8 2.2.2 didn't actually turn concurrency on by default, flake8
2.2.3 does.

The move to flake8 2.2.3 is done in two steps since our
global-requirements system does now allow for non-overlapping changes.

Bug: https://bitbucket.org/tarek/flake8/issue/163/
Change-Id: I676dbf2402922112923d63a98b1aae85abe0331a
"}]
commit_message:
Add flake8 2.2.3

Flake8 2.2.2 didn't actually turn concurrency on by default, flake8
2.2.3 does.

The move to flake8 2.2.3 is done in two steps since our
global-requirements system does now allow for non-overlapping changes.

Bug: https://bitbucket.org/tarek/flake8/issue/163/
Change-Id: I676dbf2402922112923d63a98b1aae85abe0331a

commit_message:
Add Pint for Horizon

Add the Pint package to global requirements. It is needed for unit
conversion support in Horizon's charts:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96800/

Pint project homepage: http://pint.readthedocs.org/
GitHub repo: https://github.com/hgrecco/pint

Pint is a pure python package without any external dependencies.
It is python3 compliant and has BSD license.

Partially implements: blueprint ceilometer-api-statistics-decorators-and-convertors

Change-Id: Ic9683c7a28cb9db008a974cde2daa57c9abcad61

commit_message:
memcached: switch leader election implementation to a lock

We reuse our lock code to manage the leader election, a.k.a. eat our own
dog food.

This also fixes the issue that all lock were not released when stop()
was called.

Change-Id: Ibbec3e8ac29d55247ec3b1b8941d5a9569b67677

commit_message:
Change v3 admin-password to v2.1

This patch changes v3 admin-password API to v2.1 and backport v3
unit test cases to v2.1.
The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api
Change-Id: I167753eddd188120236c51bade549c907c8a8466

commit_message:
Adding quotas on alarms

+ Quotas can be set at a user level or a project level
+ Quotas are set via config options
+ Quotas default values are None (unlimited) for backward compatibility
+ Creates a new client side error OverQuota that is raised when the
  quota is reached
+ If OverQuota is raised, return a HTTP 403 (forbidden) response.

Change-Id: Ib9876013f8eb930875a91699a6b3314f8f1b1b47
Implements: blueprint quotas-on-alarms
Co-Authored-By: Ala Rezmerita <ala.rezmerita@cloudwatt.com>

commit_message:
Update environment statuses

* Do not create session in case of observing environment applications
* Forbid redeployment after failed deploy since it's not working
* Do not show 'Deploy Environment' when environment status is 'ready'

Change-Id: I90a673d82c528ea9f05dfe1967d6c5d3d1df228c
Closes-Bug: #1342404

commit_message:
Working on engine implementation: start_workflow()

* Implementation of DefaultEngine.start_workflow()
* Unit tests
* Fixing DB models
* Adding new module for Data Flow operations

TODO:
* on_task_result()
* Fully integrated Data Flow
* Take care of ad-hoc actions

Change-Id: I55b7760ce09f40d5ccce51969c876c175bf66840

commit_message:
Upgrades, fix iptables cleaning in docker engine

Rules should be cleaned after we start
new container via supervisor because
after containers creation we stop all
of the containers and start them again
under supervisor.

Change-Id: I6272b2fd93f1180cddb15f7a4ceca4d1c55d02b7
Related-bug: #1349287

commit_message:
Support Neutron DVR installation

To facilitate support for Neutron DVR, it will be necessary to
install the neutron-l3-agent and neutron-metadata-agent on the
compute nodes.  This change pulls installation of the l3-agent
and metadata-agent out from the neutron-network-node element to
a new 'neutron-router' element which does not list a dependency
on the neutron-dhcp-agent element.  In this way, the neutron-
router element can be specified for the compute node image build
when supporting Neutron DVR.

Additionally, some new configuration values need to be added in
the neutron.conf, l3_agent.ini and ml2_conf.ini image elements to
add needed parameter settings.

Change-Id: Ia9e71ebe3cfcb7b5be54d11b7852177911d69239

commit_message:
Fix dump_cib method for corosync service provider

Corosync_service.rb is missing block_until_ready() call
in its dump_cib method. That might result in empty xml result.

Closes-bug: #1355816

Change-Id: I757522b297e0025cee7de3130743e0ef6a6fb77b
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

I like this approach, I already feel that lack when writing other functional tests.'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-08-18 08:34:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think that unless we configure the gate to run with the system-wide binaries we're going to run into a lot of trouble, this being the first. I'm not knowledgeable about the technical details / implications, though. Maru, can you pinpoint the disadvantage of running with the system wide binaries? I think it's closer to a real deployment, it requires no changes to the rootwrap filters, and it's less risky / more future proof."}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2014-08-18 14:21:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Assaf: Running with system-wide binaries would require breaking the isolation that tox provides.  Either the binaries that tox deploys would have to be deleted before the test run (so that the binaries deployed by devstack could be used), or the python path they target would have to be rewritten (say, with a sed command).  While that approach would work, I think it would be more invasive and potentially surprising than the approach proposed in this patch.

The potential drawback to this change's approach is that KillFilter won't be testable in the functional suite, but that doesn't preclude ensuring coverage in integration tests."}, {'account_id': 12737, 'date': '2014-08-18 15:16:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add hook scripts for the functional infra job

Infra jobs support hooks to customize behavior.  This change adds
scripts that are intended to be called by the neutron-dsvm-functional
jobs as hooks.   Defining hook behavior in-tree instead of directly in
the job definition has the advantage of allowing changes in hook
behavior to be tested before merge.

The gate_hook.sh script added by this change installs a rootwrap
filter to allow functional tests to destroy python processes that
they have spawned.  The tests use the python executable provided by
their tox env, and the default rootwrap configuration does not
support killing processes launched by non-system python executables.

This change will have to merge to master and stable/icehouse before
the supporting infra config change can be merged:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116458/

Partial-bug: #1360658
Change-Id: Idcc6195f91fac833c14892f27fb793048ef964b9

commit_message:
Fix HA mode troubles with Heat

HAProxy configuration doesn't include Heat services CFN and
Cloudwatch API (on port 8000 and 8003) as a result this services
unavailable via public interface.

Change-Id: Iafb5c119445e37e85b2f0d95b38aaee3b2e14b45

commit_message:
Fix post_start_hooks entry point, add purge to setup hook

post_start_hooks was calling post_setup_hooks,
which is a misnomer. post_setup_hooks should also
call purge because it is necessary during upgrades.

Change-Id: Ic8731f185338b6febd9c543f837ffed2abec80a5
Partial-Bug: #1349287

commit_message:
SoftwareDeployments move signal reason into resource plugin

Move the determination of the signal reason string inside the resource
plugin so we don't need the resource-specific details handling in the
base-class.

Change-Id: I1eec87c2063a1958eba2ad32d43474c2ed435117
Related-Bug: #1340894

commit_message:
Direct dnsmasq logs to file for Cobbler

Since rsyslog does not run in Cobbler
docker container, its logs should be
directed to a file.

Change-Id: I9cf9dd9baca5d09e26bb315211eccf6fe74060b4
Closes-Bug: #1357408

Yes!'}, {'account_id': 11324, 'date': '2014-08-25 22:05:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I like the change but I think this change is incomplete.

Ideally we would like [testenv:pep8] section to have just flake8 command. We have overloaded this section by adding check_uptodate.sh and check_for_alembic_branches.sh scripts. Clearly the intention was to run these additional sanity checks for newly added code. By moving check_uptodate.sh script to [testenv:uptodate] section, this is okay for local testing but solum gate no longer checks for config discrepencies.
My recommendation:
(1) Move overloaded scripts in pep8 section to new section 'misc' (or 'ext'/extended-checks or 'sanity' or some other better name).
Changes might look like:
envlist=pypy,pep8,py26,py27,py33,misc  

[testenv:pep8]
commands = flake8

[testenv:misc]
commands = 
  .../check_uptodate.sh
  .../check_for_alembic_branches.sh
(2) Add a new gate job, gate-solum-misc (voting) to openstack-infra/config project (modules/openstack_project/files/zuul/layout.yaml)


So far, check_uptodate.sh script never worked on my vagrant box. Always fails with
<error snippet>
$ tox -e pep8
...
check_uptodate.sh: solum.conf.sample is not up to date.
check_uptodate.sh: Please run /opt/stack/solum/tools/config/generate_sample.sh.
ERROR: InvocationError: '/opt/stack/solum/tools/config/check_uptodate.sh'
</error>
Running generate_sample.sh first and then check_uptodate.sh works though.Let me know if you know the issue, thanks."}, {'account_id': 1375, 'date': '2014-08-25 22:13:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1375, 'date': '2014-08-25 22:18:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

See, the alembic script never failed for me, it was the check-uptodate one since the sample conf gets mangled when I install everything on my dev environment.

This latest patch pulls both of those checks into their own environment, but keeps them as part of the run env list when tox is run. I think that should be enough to keep all the checks running on the gate. Let's find out!"}, {'account_id': 11324, 'date': '2014-08-25 23:09:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

AFAICT, you need to update openstack-infra/config
We may get +1 from jenkins but it ignores these new sections.
Adding to 'envlist' in tox.ini will work if the caller does just 'tox'. If you look at current gate jobs (any pull request) and check each of its console log, it does 'tox -e <specific-command>'.

Individual sections is great for local testing but adding gate jobs for each section will be inefficient, Zuul will be spending more time in creating the test env for each job (actual script might be very small).
I'll propose one more option:
- We can have separate sections like pep8, uptodate, alembicbranches (what you did in this patch) and this will be helpful in local testing
- Club commands in pep8, uptodate and alembicbranches sections and create a new section [testenv:sanity] (same as original code, just 'pep8' is renamed to 'sanity'). Update/rename gate-solum-pep8 to gate-solum-sanity in openstack-infra/config (This will minimize unnecessary overhead and I think that's why these scripts are overloaded in the first place!)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-26 03:28:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Move sanity checks out of pep tox env

Moves check_uptodate and check_for_alembic_branches
to their own tox environments, so the pep8 check only
checks for flake8 compliance.

The other checks are still available, albeit in their own
respective environments. By naming them in the envlist,
they will still run when "tox" on its own is called.

commit_message:
Enabling Heat provisioning based on ENV for Trove

Reasons:
 - Trove can use Heat as resource delivery service.
   Heat support can be enabled by setting
   `use_heat=True` in trove-taskmanager.conf,
   in [DEFAULT] section;
 - required for bulding Trove gate with enabled Heat-provisioning.

Changes:
 - adding HEAT_PROVISIONING_SUPPORT variable in lib/trove
   that relays on ENV variable HEAT_PROVISIONING_SUPPORT;
 - if HEAT_PROVISIONING_SUPPORT is not set - use False by the default.
 - added description at samples/local.conf

Change-Id: Ie0426cd0113db5f9513bafa8c0f4bd3004eaa1a1

commit_message:
labs: increase RAM allocation for compute node

Running a default instance on the compute node uses 512 MB RAM, which is
all of the compute node's RAM.

This patch increases the RAM allocation for the compute node to 1024 MB,
enabling it to run an instance.

Change-Id: I59ef85b2680f8b68d08108d738e03a964457680c

commit_message:
Trying to ingore races related to Nova + restoring missing benchmark

Seems like Nova has some fix related to checking default security group
to avoid it we can add more tenants in 2 benchmarks that are failing
boot_and_bounce_server and boot_and_resize

Restore nova-boot with nics

Change-Id: If625910a581afba0224e4ac591373d132d7f8efd

commit_message:
labs: fix getopts use in osbash.sh

For invalid options, $opt contains a literal '?' rather than the option
itself. This patch disables the builtin error message, which gets us
the invalid option passed as OPTARG.

Change-Id: I3b0d3d85e6c95f1839eed19679bf4d8af378cc29

commit_message:
Fix issue with periodic fail of Heat test 'test_autoscaling'

-Increased alarms period in templates
-Increased number of RAM in test flavor

Closes-Bug: #1361629

commit_message:
skip polls if service is not registered

currently, when any pollster runs against a service that is not
registered in Keystone, it will throw an exception. we should
catch and skip these polls

Change-Id: I2b582b22a44182ab31d44ce459cc6d642cc3719d
Closes-Bug: #1337293

commit_message:
Check the url format when create endpoint

In the process of creating an endpoint, the URL was not verified,
and anyone could add a malformed URL.

Change-Id: I2ede39148e19d816d049307a90b6114f5541c5c3
Closes-Bug: #1284430

commit_message:
Install files properly

It's not a good idea to install files/* to /etc/httpd/conf.d/ because
all elements get copied into one place, so this could copy unexpected files.

Instead copy files individually, from a fully-structured path in files/,
to minimise the chance of filename collisions.

This issue was observed during CI of
I95da168ee56ef05ea7a75db2135bebd642b13588.

Change-Id: Ib792afb2b011da9f18d4ef2a1deacbc5f9d57d11

commit_message:
Hide multicast related attributes

Attributes for multicast should be hidden for user
because multicast verification is disabled for 5.1

I prefer not to delete it to avoid additional data
migration in 6.0 release

Change-Id: I7e601b65499ddbecd566b4597290de18284f9006
Closes-Bug: 1360018

commit_message:
Disable sshd GSSAPI auth

GSSAPI is not currently implemented in Fuel, so
it only slows incoming SSH connections. Disabling
it will enhance user experience.

Change-Id: I935e7c383e24663296c938e32b12682086d6797b
Closes-Bug: #1327988

commit_message:
Fix HA mode troubles with Heat

HAProxy configuration doesn't include Heat services CFN and
Cloudwatch API (on port 8000 and 8003) as a result this services
unavailable via public interface.

Change-Id: Iafb5c119445e37e85b2f0d95b38aaee3b2e14b45
Closes-bug: #1353348

commit_message:
Force volumes to rebuild after cluster reset

* rewritten `reset_environment_resp` to use objects
* after each cluster reset volumes configuration will be rebuild
  to prevent issues when disks identifiers will change
  after reset

Change-Id: I518a2ad36248b9a676455e8f43ac9f3f76515871
Closes-Bug: #1359070
Closes-Bug: #1360248

commit_message:
Consolidated devstack script

Based on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110988/

One script to run tests on devstack for both murano components:
* murano-engine
* murano-dashboard
* python-muranoclient

Nodepool preparation script included.

Use separate tests for murano-dashboard because of a bug in horizon
    https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1351298

Change-Id: I4f424cca68f0dcce8a1052f61703f4dc9891cb97

commit_message:
Exit rabbitmq container if puppet apply fails

Puppet now runs for rabbitmq container with
detailed exitcodes, allowing us to fail start
of container with start.sh. Sometimes restarting
the container will resolve rare issues where
rabbitmq service doesn't start from its init script.

Change-Id: I108cc4521fa7e193c68ede466b5829ad33464224
Closes-Bug: #1358972

[{'created': '2014-08-22 16:37:43.000000000', 'message': 'Update stack-preview usage text

`--timeout` during stack-preview is only used in certain validation
paths and `--enable-rollback` is not used at all except to be consistent
with stack-create.  This changes the usage text to reflect these
peculiarities.

Change-Id: I9eafad207075f70b1321bb3559cb1363fe526f85
'}]
commit_message:
Update stack-preview usage text

`--timeout` during stack-preview is only used in certain validation
paths and `--enable-rollback` is not used at all except to be consistent
with stack-create.  This changes the usage text to reflect these
peculiarities.

Change-Id: I9eafad207075f70b1321bb3559cb1363fe526f85

commit_message:
labs: reattach shared dirs after export

Shared directories are removed when exporting VMs to an OVA file. This
patch reattaches the shared directories after the VMs haven been
exported.

Change-Id: I3527aac6958df906e2aac8d95744b2362e8660f9

commit_message:
labs: don't source labs-openstackrc.sh

Setup_neutron_network.sh attempts to source a file that has been
renamed. Because the script doesn't need authentication, we can
just remove the reference to the file.

Change-Id: Ie5c1c6bf8bda87b0e7cca9ec92aa86c53e866ff4

labs: exit after unhandled option

With this patch, it does.

commit_message:
Updates Nova under training labs

Updates to nova, fixes some of the issues present in the scripts.

Changes the compute package from "nova-compute-kvm" to
"nova-compute-qemu".

Fixes Bug 1312764
Implements Blueprint: openstack-training-labs

commit_message:
VMware: handle case when VM snapshot delete fails

Minesweeper fails on occasion with concurrent access to files.

If a snapshot deletion fails with the backend exception
TaskInProgress then we will retry.

A generic decorator has been added to do the retry operations.

Closes-bug: #1310817

Change-Id: I8ed7a24ccd34aeea49352ac98f34ec2960edbf97

commit_message:
Fix haproxy backend checks dependencies

Openstack::Ha::Haproxy_service['keystone*']
should always be evaluated *before* any
Exec['wait-for-keystone*'] backend checks.

Closes-bug: 1352964

Change-Id: I579f33d673925bea27ceab48f3380ed1dda40170
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix tests dependency on config datastores and version

Reasons:
 - Int tests are dependent on config-based
   datastores and version, that are already stored in DB

Changes:
 - Fixing tests to use datastores and version from DB
   (through datastores API).

Change-Id: I0ea471df6358203e97b8ca65f920ce8d4b65201d
Closes-Bug: #1329347

commit_message:
Make turning debug on globally easy.

We can obviously use passthrough for this, but I rather suspect that
OMFG something is broken get me debug will be a common phrase.

This is a version for if we revert the HOT migration.

Change-Id: I62539630a4737bbbe6883ed71929f38c819ceed5

commit_message:
Implement full heat integration

Reasons:
 - Trove should be able to manage resource provisioning through:
     - nova, cinder, designate etc. (navites);
     - heat. (orchestration).
     - Main reason is to provide harmless migration from the nova to heat,
       when heat would be cover all required use cases such as
       provisioning/resizing/network-attributes-management.

Changes:
 - Refactoring:
   - dividing actual manager onto navite(nova/cinder/designate/neutron)
     and orchestrator(heat);
   - extracting common code into taskmanager/common.py
   - fixing tests;
   - Resize instance for orchestrator added;
   - Resize volume for orchestrator added.
 - tox.ini modified to run all tests for natives or orchestration.

Change-Id: Ia9001877b1538e42bf81bec4e9947bf232547c06
Implements: blueprint full-heat-integration

commit_message:
Add stack_id to base instance model

Reasons:
 - saving stack id would give to trove an
   ability to perform actions such as
   stack update/delete;

Changes:
 - adding stack_id column into base schema;
 - DBInstance model update.

Change-Id: Ie723a3c41e5ced19788a310cf727e1c143df6a62
Implements: blueprint stack-id

commit_message:
Change overcloud to use VIP for MySQL

This change sets applications to utilize the VIP address for database
connectivity and sets HAProxy in between the applications and MySQL.

This is a non-HOT version for unblocking CI deployments.

implements: blueprint tripleo-icehouse-ha-production-configuration
Change-Id: Ia9d6ed2771f756d2a97ae5df7ed737a062a59cf3

commit_message:
Add openvswitch-datapath mapping for redhat

On redhat family distros, there is no openvswitch-datapath
packaged (support for tunneling is already included in the kernel)

Change-Id: I0c7703518f226fb7adb3f85cfd7c07aa43ffe236

commit_message:
Fix rabbitmqctl status for rabbitmq container

Set RABBITMQ_NODENAME according to container hostname to make sure
"rabbitmqctl" command works properly.

Change-Id: Iedec5661da5029cd89ab2067bdcb582787275a90
Closes-bug: #1335041

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-19 20:10:12.000000000', 'message': 'Permit specifying VLAN mappings to overclouds.

Sadly this will often need to be user controlled (to restrict the VLANs
to ones the network admins have allocated) - because while admin API
credentials are needed, its the mapping in the ovs plugin that actually
restricts what networks can operate - and defense in depth is a fairly
important security approach.

The default changes in the associated bridge mapping so that we can
fix a long standing configuration glitch where our ext-net is actually
defined as a gre overlay network!!!

Change-Id: I9687751753f810896c6d065750910da40132c9fa
'}, {'created': '2014-07-19 21:07:42.000000000', 'message': 'Permit specifying VLAN mappings to overclouds.

Sadly this will often need to be user controlled (to restrict the VLANs
to ones the network admins have allocated) - because while admin API
credentials are needed, its the mapping in the ovs plugin that actually
restricts what networks can operate - and defense in depth is a fairly
important security approach.

To use this we also need to change the defaults for bridge and flat
network mapping - and this happens to also permit fixing a long standing
configuration glitch where our ext-net is actually defined as a gre overlay
network!

Change-Id: I9687751753f810896c6d065750910da40132c9fa
'}, {'created': '2014-07-19 22:11:17.000000000', 'message': "Permit specifying VLAN mappings to overclouds.

To use a VLAN based public network we need the ext-net network to be a
VLAN with a segmentation id - but we can't do this unless we also have
the datacentre datacentre physical network marked as allowing vlans.

We could make this strictly opt-in, but as this doesn't affect the
switch configuration (and thus actual machine capabilities) having it
on by default seems reasonable. OTOH we can't force it on, because
high security environments may well want a defense in depth setup
where neutron admins cannot configure VLANs that they are not meant
to have access too (consider that the cloud machine admins may be
separate to the folk running the services on top of them...)

commit_message:
Permit specifying VLAN mappings to overclouds.

To use a VLAN based public network we need the ext-net network to be a
VLAN with a segmentation id - but we can't do this unless we also have
the datacentre physical network marked as allowing vlans.

We could make this strictly opt-in, but as this doesn't affect the
switch configuration (and thus actual machine capabilities) having it
on by default seems reasonable. OTOH we can't force it on, because
high security environments may well want a defense in depth setup
where neutron admins cannot configure VLANs that they are not meant
to have access too (consider that the cloud machine admins may be
separate to the folk running the services on top of them...)

Change-Id: I9687751753f810896c6d065750910da40132c9fa

commit_message:
Add the iptables rule to allow gre traffic

Currently there's no rule to accept gre packets which are required for the
Neutron GRE networking case, so they are dropped due to the '999 drop all' rule

Change-Id: Ia79b6e8b26a8ccf7846affbd2dbf6aa758ac4947
Closes-bug: #1355794

commit_message:
Wait for keystone to become ready for floatingip creation

Wait for keystone service to become ready otherwise
haproxy reload can lead to haproxy returning
empty response and thus nova-floating-range provider
can not authorize with nova.

Change-Id: I8f9623411990679560b1694569dbb185883c4733
Closes-bug: 1351253
Closes-bug: 1348171

commit_message:
Refactor type_tunnel/gre/vxlan to reduce duplicate code

gre and vxlan type drivers have similar implementation for multiple
methods. This change abstracts these methods and move them to
TunnelTypeDriver.

sync_allocations method is not shared between gre and vxlan type drivers
because they use different strategies and the targeted one is unclear.

Change-Id: I717b70eb718f7ae82f1bc0c81543b0c438e8bddd

commit_message:
Add copy and revert commands to dockerctl

Revert: resets to latest image for container
Copy: copy files in and out of container
  Syntax:
    dockerctl copy src dest
    Only one of src or dest may be a container path
  New function examples:
    dockerctl copy /root/newpkg.rpm nailgun:/root/
    dockerctl copy nailgun:/etc/nailgun/settings.yaml /root/

Change-Id: Ia3cc999f6dc706b83d840a0e54c976c1bde2b6d4

commit_message:
Add list function to dockerctl

New dockerctl functions:
dockerctl list - outputs short name of each
available container
dockerctl list -l - outputs short name, image name,
status, and long container name of each container

Partial-Bug: #1324227

Change-Id: I30646db6d04bf8ff1f232c7e3021d790ec5d566a

An issue occurs on certain deployment types
(mainly virtual) that causes cobbler sync to
fail because httpd is not ready yet. Adding a
service check should cover this case.

Change-Id: I9e3a45089e25a7f8400a17faee0bfc1640580849
Closes-Bug: #1338552
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure web service starts before cobbler sync

An issue occurs on certain deployment types
(mainly virtual) that causes cobbler sync to
fail because httpd is not ready yet. Adding a
service check should cover this case.

Change-Id: I9e3a45089e25a7f8400a17faee0bfc1640580849
Closes-Bug: #1338552

commit_message:
Flake8: Fix F841

Enable F841 and fix all issues.

Flake F841 is:
F841 local variable 'XXX' is assigned to but never used

Also fix in changed files some occurences of:
E128 continuation line under-indented for visual indent
H404  multi line docstring should start without a leading new line
H405  multi line docstring summary not separated with an empty line

Change-Id: Ifb08a82d05ac15c8e90f214a96e73d82ff850018
Partial-Bug: #1333290

commit_message:
Fix obtaining of service VM ip

service_instance module fails when VM in Nova is up, but get response from
Nova does not include network data. Expected field 'networks' is empty.
Fix is workaround for nova/neutron b_u_g #1210483

Change-Id: I4e066a07bb35ce85c2ac4513fbf027c9e84d5aa2
Closes-Bug: #1348632

commit_message:
Cmode, CIFS shares, fix allowed share access type

Cmode driver using CIFS helper checks rules for type and allows only old 'sid'
type that was changed to 'user' recently. After rebase to latest master it
became incompatible.

Change-Id: Ibce0ce84dc0a987839da1d546dc819c01baf7bc7

[{'created': '2014-08-19 14:00:01.000000000', 'message': 'Share common test settings in test_flavor_manage

In PrivateFlavorManageTest, there are duplicated test setting code in each
test. This patch moves these settings into setUp() method to reduce code.
In addition, this patch adds an internal method also for the same purpose.

Change-Id: I31883497174141ac4034922981e0a846f1fc2deb
'}]
commit_message:
Share common test settings in test_flavor_manage

In PrivateFlavorManageTest, there are duplicated test setting code in each
test. This patch moves these settings into setUp() method to reduce code.
In addition, this patch adds an internal method also for the same purpose.

Change-Id: I31883497174141ac4034922981e0a846f1fc2deb

filter: add per-aggregate filter to configure max_io_ops_per_host

to read from aggregates metadata "max_io_ops_per_host".

commit_message:
Fix V2 unit tests to test hypervisor API as admin

Hypervisors API are Admin API and unit tests should test those accordingly.
But All the V2 hypervisors Unit tests tests those as a non Admin API

This patch fix this issue and add more non-admin unit tests

Change-Id: I5c29828d567e2044786d4bcbff4970219c6e8c5f
Closes-Bug: #1360113

VMware: spawn refactor _configure_config_drive

Factor out the code to configure the virtual machine with a new
config drive iso image.

commit_message:
VMware: refactor spawn() code to build a new VM

Move the spawn() code which builds a new VM into
vmops.build_virtual_machine().

We remove the duplicate check of instance_name. Other than that this
is straight code motion.

In addition, we add a basic test of the function of
build_virtual_machine, which tests that all given configuration is
reflected in the resulting virtual machine.

This change has been split out of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87002/, which was written by Shawn
Hartsock.

partial blueprint vmware-spawn-refactor

Co-authored-by: Shawn Hartsock <hartsocks@acm.org>
Change-Id: Id9c95966eefb644fdaf36465e7b3d3583826314a

commit_message:
VMware: Fix type of VM's config.hardware.device in fake

config.hardware.device was handled inconsistently, and could be of
various types. When created by _create_vm(), it was actually a
VirtualDeviceConfigSpec[]. It should be a VirtualDevice[].

Fix tests which depended on the wrong type.

Add _create_array_of_type function to fake to create an array type
which works correctly when passed to code. A returned array of Foo
must be an instance of class ArrayOfFoo, and contain a single
property, Foo, which is a python array of objects of type Foo.

Change-Id: Ic90e1d0d947941621606fded9e56f9a98d111cad

commit_message:
VMware: Create fake VM with given datastore

FakeVim._create_vm() was creating a VM with a default datastore rather
than the given one. This prevented testing that the correct datastore
has been used.

Change-Id: I640a21f23b2d5c1186772c8c5ce3ca8927e6cbc5

commit_message:
Add management interface for agent drivers

This commit adds management interface for the agent drivers
AgentAndIPMIToolDriver and AgentAndIPMINativeDriver, which is
required for setting boot device.

Change-Id: I90a9277357e490761567b76e13ca33da65ba476d
Closes-Bug: #1360224

commit_message:
Remove docutils pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

Change-Id: I6ea61a3cc441dd1ca2ced7e2fd837a55b917f76d

Improve logging in sessions.py

* Fix info log level to error
* Pass an explanation to the exception

Closes-Bug; #1359188

commit_message:
Re-order stack.sh 2: target dir setup

Part 2 of a series

Re-order the setup and check bits in the top portion of stack.sh to
have a logical flow with similar things done together.

No behaviour changes are intended aside from the order of execution.
Any such changes are bugs.

* Consolidate DEST dir setup
* Move rpc & database init to just before project init

commit_message:
Reload iptables after purging rules, add rsyslog to post_start_hooks

In some cases, rsyslog would only unmasquerade UDP connections
and not TCP connections, causing issues with deployment.

This commit includes fixes for purging old iptables
rules that run into race conditions, as well as a fix
for grep to include '--' to handle strings that
start with dash.

Change-Id: I3913cb2ebd7fee42039e280f676b80f8f36e1841
Closes-Bug: #1360298

commit_message:
Remove docutils pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

Add PYTHONHASHSEED to tox.ini so that testsuite passes.

Change-Id: I6ea61a3cc441dd1ca2ced7e2fd837a55b917f76d

commit_message:
Add feature_request mechanism

This will be standart way for end users to ask Rally team to get
some new feature.

The idea is to make it realy simple for end users to ask about covering
their use cases.

E.g. to add request users don't need to deep dive in rally community,
road map and how it works. They need just to share their use cases
that is not covered by current rally functionality.

As a bonus adding some Readme.rst files related to doc/* dirs

Change-Id: I4c615101012ac9d1668ed766ac831f7e5c8129a8

commit_message:
Make rabbitmq autoheal partitions

Default policy is 'ignore' and it does nothing in order
to recover from partitioning allowing many partitioned
rabbit clusters to operate as is.
Auto-heal policy will merge all partitions into the winner
one once exited from partitioned state
(e.g. connectivity restored).

Closes-bug: #1354319

Change-Id: I33823a3abfd42b75fa6bc73d6f3cd038a2163fd6
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Force chown for log files before starting rabbitmq

For some reason log files /var/log/rabbitmq/startup_log and
/var/log/rabbitmq/shutdown_log becomes owned be root,
preventing rabbitmq-server for murano (launched from 'rabbitmq' user)
from writing to them.

Change-Id: Ifa3d3484e3f22fe97cdb747c2c58f2d408246f32
Closes-bug: #1360264

commit_message:
Use murano-db-manage to run upgrades

In previous versions of Murano the command used to manage database
was 'murano-manage'. Now it is changed to 'murano-db-manage', however,
'murano-manage' still exists.

This patch fixes the name of the command, and renames variable used to
store path to 'murano-db-manage' to avoid confusion between the two
available commands.

Closes-bug: #1358738

Change-Id: Ib8a7a1f126a15c419dd8b6d27e5dd32bb5196b32

commit_message:
Update requirements, fix testsuite

Manually update from global requirements.
Remove obsolete docutils pin.
Regenerate climate config file.
Fix testsuite for testtools change.
Workaround PYTHONHASHSEED setting in tox, disable for now so that tests
always pass.

Change-Id: I8c4a458371b28c91c5b848094e56038a16d6afc3

commit_message:
Use oslo.db create_engine instead of SQLAlchemy

oslo.db may set additional options to engines that we may be interested in.

blueprint enable-mysql-connector

Closes-Bug: #1350942
Change-Id: I6f67bb430c50ddacb2d53398de75fb5f494964a0

commit_message:
Log exceptions inside spawned functions

eventlet pool will discards all exception raised inside spawn(_n), it is
hard to discover problems inside spawned green-threads, it is better to
add a function wrapper to log the exceptions raised inside spawned
function.

Change-Id: I753df36c4614759f49134667a55f2a91f0c08317
Closes-bug: #1340708

commit_message:
Removing sorted() function from assertEqual()

Removing unnecessary sorted() function from assertEqual() function
calls in functions used for sorting and pagination testing

Using sorted() breaks sorting tests objective which is to test sorting.
This is causing every unit test using this functions
(_test_list_with_sort, _test_list_with_pagination, _test_list_with_pagination_reverse)
for sorting tests to always succeed

Switched the parameters for assertEqual() function within the fixed code to meet
its signature - assertEqual(self, expected, observed, message='')

Test neutron.tests.unit.vmware.vshield.test_lbaas_plugin.TestLoadbalancerPlugin.test_list_vips
was succeeding because of this bug, although it should fail. It failed after the bug was fix.
Test was fixed.

Change-Id: Ia36b81d9a7fd32cae3b567ac1899b56481eb62ce
Closes-Bug: #1355251

commit_message:
Do not assume order of parameters in OVSBridge.add_flow call

This fixes neutron.tests.unit.agent.linux.test_ovs_lib.OVS_Lib_Test.test_add_flow
unit test that breaks with a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED.

The test assumed that the parameters passed to add_flow had
elements in a particular order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=2455351445.
The fix refactors the test case to match parameters as set.

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with a
randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will be
addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: Ibe2f4d929b8b42c8c909c2306d2554faf7109b49

List users doesn't support filtering by email

The Identity API v3 reference document said that a user could
filter the list users response by email, but this isn't supported.

Change-Id: I1d89e34ea6c54f46bd5b2424ee332f02d843433e
Closes-Bug: #1306835

commit_message:
Upgrades, fix astute keys migration

In some cases ssh keys copying fails
* user installs env and doesn't run
  deployment
* he runs upgrade
* it fails
* users runs it again
* it cannot copy keys and fails

The reason is, upgrade script had
a condition which reraised the
exception if directory existed.

As result we create empty directory
if there was an error.

Closes-bug: #1361284
Change-Id: Id30bc3bd8628cf6d6747c52a210f7abe9b94ca99

commit_message:
Specify endpoint_type in telemetry install guide

In compute node, os_endpoint_type should be set to internalURL in
ceilometer.conf when controller management ip is used

Closes-bug: 1320817

commit_message:
Fix HA mode troubles with Heat

HAProxy configuration doesn't include Heat services CFN and
Cloudwatch API (on port 8000 and 8003) as a result this services
unavailable via public interface.

Change-Id: I2b29a20be1cbd6f52e6d358b1e4075d3f7e73784
Closes-bug: #1353348

commit_message:
Updated usage for stack-preview rollback param

The --enable-rollback parameter was added to stack-preview command
for maintaining symmetry with the stack-create command in changeId
Ifda2b6bdf2380ce22c6f2027ea8ee4e6e977cf60.
Updated the usage text for stack-preview command to reflect that
the parameter does not affect the behavior of preview operation.

Change-Id: Ifcff7b7f3241d41e99491f1a6781569343e2dc56

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-31 05:32:29.000000000', 'message': 'Unset HTTP_PROXY before running tests

urllib2 uses $http_proxy and requests uses $HTTP_PROXY.  If either of
these are set (and pointing to a remote host), then any tests that try
to spin up a local server and connect to it using
http://127.0.0.1:$port/ will try to connect to $port *on the proxy*, and
presumably fail.

We could hunt down and find all such tests and provide the appropriate
options to ignore HTTP_PROXY, but just fixing it globally here is easier
and more robust.

Note also that tox will still see $HTTP_PROXY and presumably use it for

commit_message:
Ignore http_proxy while connecting to test WSGI server

urllib2.urlopen uses $http_proxy/$HTTP_PROXY environment variables by
default.  If set (and pointing to a remote host), then the WSGI tests
that spin up a local server and connect to it using
http://127.0.0.1:$port/ instead connect to $port *on the proxy*,
and (hopefully) fail.

This change uses urllib2 in a way that ignores proxy settings.

Change-Id: I4d94fcc06925d0c947345a07ae20352e1898e46d
Closes-Bug: #1356665

So the API docs state that both these are supported by the API, so I guess it's fine to add it to the client:

http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-orchestration-v1.html

The timeout value could possibly be used in some validation paths (although I'm not aware of any non-runtime validation atm).

commit_message:
Added timeout and rollback params in stack-preview

Added the support to specify timeout and enable_rollback
parameters to the stack-preview command.

Change-Id: Ifda2b6bdf2380ce22c6f2027ea8ee4e6e977cf60
Closes-Bug: #1335098

commit_message:
javelin: add security groups support

Create and check that security groups survive at upgrades.

- Create security groups and rules
- Assign a security group after server creation
- Check security groups survive after upgrade

Change-Id: I7a8304782697d15f4201164695c321aa38097c17
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Only document the wrapper usage, since it handles all the environment

commit_message:
Update the autohelp readme

Switch to RST.

Only document the wrapper usage, since it handles all the environment
setup and is easier to use than the python scripts.

Add a requirements.txt file to ease the setup process and documentation.

Change-Id: Icc4f9cb4dfcaae6df8cd2567cc9b8f46fda0600c

commit_message:
Fix for floatingip-delete not removing fip_gw port

fip_agent_gateway_port is created dynamically on a
compute node where FIP namespace is created. When
floatingip-disassociate is called this 'port' is
deleted.

But when we call floatingip-delete this port is
not deleted.

This patch fixes the issue mentioned above.

Closes-Bug: #1351066

Change-Id: I1aa51680394547390546fe362abfae7a5d25425b

commit_message:
Enhance V3 version controller to provide JSON Home response

The V3 version controller would only respond with the normal version
JSON response. With this change, if the Accept header is
`application/json-home` it will respond with a JSON Home response
which includes all the registered JSON Home data. Note that there is
no JSON Home data yet so the response is empty.

bp json-home

Change-Id: Icfde89040b376bd6704d497966bd8ad109e32d08

subject: Fix handling of missing external network

commit_message:
Fix handling of missing external network

When an external network can't be found, project/routers/index.html will
result in a type error caused by calling exceptions.handle when no
exception is present.  In this case, an error message should be
displayed, and the missing-network should be indicated to the user.

Also added tests for this case.

Change-Id: I3aaa64de28738051ad84cc587fbb6cfd546f4662
Closes-Bug: 1220345

commit_message:
Import registry's API to register the options

1ac30bbd667aa5266ddb2967198dceba787a6653 improved the way db_api options
are registered and as part of the change, the import of the registry api
in the test_registry suite was removed. Although the changes in that
commit work fine for Glance, they don't work that well for this test
suite since the `load_tests` function just registers the functions to
use for loading the database API without calling them. Unfortunately,
this causes the test registry to fail while trying to register the
registry client's options.

This patch adds the import back. A better solution will be added in a
follow-up patch. Such fix would require changing other db_api tests,
hence this patch is being proposed as a first fix.

Change-Id: I235d3f17242cb13e7c7480b835f67fc453a2dc54

commit_message:
Make swiftclient a requirement

Since there's a glance migration depending on swift and the swift store
is also widely used, this patch proposes making swiftclient a strong
dependency for glance.store.

I think it would be better to keep all store specific dependencies as
optional, we can remove swiftclient later again.

Change-Id: I88ccd70692524a2e57e2e6fda0ee52552dab4524

commit_message:
Do not explicitly set mysql_engine

Setting the mysql_engine when creating a table is not needed
anymore as this is automatically done by an event listener
added with commit 466e89970f11918a809aafe8a048d138d4664299

Change-Id: I0df978dbf2bb44f17102da3c17fd4e93c9e4df8d
Closes-Bug: #1361176

My vote is of an outsider, that's why I'm not scoring: not a team member and unlikely to become one. 

Audio calls are ok for a lot of things but if we're talking about enabling an open collaboration then there is one rule to follow:

 - provide a URL with indexed, searchable text or it didn't happen

The Octavia team should provide just that. If you have a way to do that with webex, hangout, anything fancy or manually by taking religiously scrupulous notes, use them. If not, consider revert to IRC as the minimum common denominator which gives the written notes and URL for free."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:19:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

As I responded on the mailing list:  We have been sending the meeting minutes to the openstack-dev mailing list which is both indexed and searchable.  But in an effort to help newcomers get up to speed more quickly I have transposed these to the mailing list here:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Octavia/Meeting_Minutes'}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:20:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Is this the equivalent of "share for yes, like for not" for developers?

I echo Stefano's comment:
Text-searchable full logs or it did not happen.'}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:32:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

And again, I say: we have searchable, indexed text.

Also, in light of the above comments: Why do we hold OpenStack summits? Surely they're a place where people having trouble with English, or who are more soft spoken are going to have a hard time collaborating. It's also far more exclusionary than webex because there's (potentially) a hefty registration fee, as well as travel costs and time associated with participating.

Also, apparently not a lot happens at these summits because I don't see a whole lot of indexed, searchable text coming out of them. ;)"}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:36:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not teasing you... the minutes are not a full meeting log, where I can browse what everyone said. Indeed the meeting bot for IRC meetings on which we rely gives us both the minutes (built using specific commands during the meeting) and a full log.

Still, the decision is up to the team. As I've never contributed, feel free to count my vote or not."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:52:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Right. I'm just pointing out that the requirement for 'indexed searchable text' has been changed in a requirement for full transcripts of everything that was said.  I'm further pointing out that changing that requirement half-way through this discussion is hypocritical in light of the fact that OpenStack summit meetings don't get the same treatment, and I don't think anyone here would seriously argue that an amazing amount of things get accomplished in very little time at summit design sessions.

Really, we're trying to be open in our collaboration:  Webex isn't much of a bar for most people to meet, and one can cover so much more material when voice is used rather than just text that the trade-offs (especially when the project is still being bootstrapped) seem worth it.

The long-term plan is to move to IRC, but it seems to me like we'd be unnecessarily delaying the initial progress on this project by moving there too early."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:53:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sorry, "that anyone here would argue against the idea that an amazing..."

Yes, even written English is hard sometimes. :P'}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:56:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Also Salvatore (and Stefano):  I really would like it if you wanted to get involved with Octavia! We could certainly use someone with your experience and expertise, eh.'}, {'account_id': 11302, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:10:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10280, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:13:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:24:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:27:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I am ok with webex as log as we continue to have excellent meeting minutes captured.'}, {'account_id': 10477, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:27:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:38:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Michael: Yep, Trevor has been great at doing this.

Heh-- the move to IRC might just end up coinciding with whenever he gets sick of writing up the minutes himself. XD'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-08-21 21:22:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Stephen, I'm not seeing new "requirements" here, just how people like to work.  And I can say that on more than one occasion, I have:

- Read openstack meeting notes, and then gone to read the actual transcript for more detail.
- Attended openstack meetings while in situations where I couldn't have done voice (on another call, a restaurant, etc.)

Do I prefer transcripts and text to voice?  Yes, yes I do.  Are there other advantages to voice?  Yes, yes there are.  Does that change my preference?  Nope.'}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2014-08-21 21:36:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Stephen: let's not mix the issues ... maybe we should have a quick chat/call (ha!) to understand each other :) I'm not kidding: there are different tools to achieve different goals. That's the reason why all teams join the summits (and mid-cycle meetings) in person, hold discussions on sync&async communication tools (mlists, gerrit, etc, IRC, phone calls, etc).

The point of this specific changeset is about the weekly coordination meetings for Octavia's team. I think it is commonly accepted that all OpenStack projects (in general) have weekly meetings on IRC because these provide a convenient way to: hold meetings, discuss issues in near-real time, keep the full history logs and keep meeting minutes. All teams have *also* other ways to communicate and they use them, but decisions or summaries in general are always published somewhere visible (or it didn't happen). You've decided to deviate from this common behavior. There is no blame on my part, just acknowledging that you're doing things differently for the team's weekly meeting. Is that good or bad? I don't know, yet: as with so many other questions in life, the answer is 'it depends' :)

Are published minutes in text form enough, with recordings of the voice? Maybe. I know I would never listen to the full audio but I would more likely read an IRC log of a meeting (I actually do that quite often, when I see meeting minutes that catch my eye and I want to know who said what in response to what exactly)."}, {'account_id': 10750, 'date': '2014-08-21 22:32:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I prefer the most channel-rich form of communication for now.'}, {'account_id': 10280, 'date': '2014-08-21 22:52:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If and when the meetings become too large we can revisit the idea of reverting back to the archaic irc but I like having mutual exclusion when people are talking. Like how most people do in real life. I'm not a huge fan of the text conversations happening simultaneously resulting in the high speed text orgies some of these openstack-meetings are becoming as of late."}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-08-21 22:53:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

"high speed text orgies".  hahahaha, I love the phrasing.'}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-08-21 23:03:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I will go with whatever the majority wants, eh--  I would just ask that those  voting have definite intentions to involve themselves and contribute to the project, eh. commit_message:
Should we move Octavia meetings to IRC?  +1 yes, -1 webex

Pros:
- High bandwidth
- Faster
Cons:
- Much harder for non-native english speakers
- Much harder for the quieter types
- No logs

The current decision is webex, but it was made on webex, which is problematic.
Feel free to leave additional comments.

Change-Id: Ifef0547c6e01172c573a1d73fbabcb310de94a28

[{'created': '2014-08-19 23:06:27.000000000', 'message': "Provide access to outputs from OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup

Allow get_attr on OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup to return a list of
corresponding attributes from each of the base resources. For example,

  {'get_attr': ['my_asg', 'outputs_list', 'networks', '<network_name>', 0]}

will return a list of the first IP address assigned to each server in the
group. This is modelled on similar functionality in the
OS::Heat::ResourceGroup resource. Similarly:

  {'get_attr': ['my_asg', 'outputs', 'networks', '<network_name>', 0]}

returns a mapping from resource names to the corresponding IP addresses.

Change-Id: Ib9e830e0c54602ac456d64179e1df30f0778906d
Closes-bug: #1356544
"}]
commit_message:
Provide access to outputs from OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup

Allow get_attr on OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup to return a list of
corresponding attributes from each of the base resources. For example,

  {'get_attr': ['my_asg', 'outputs_list', 'networks', '<network_name>', 0]}

will return a list of the first IP address assigned to each server in the
group. This is modelled on similar functionality in the
OS::Heat::ResourceGroup resource. Similarly:

  {'get_attr': ['my_asg', 'outputs', 'networks', '<network_name>', 0]}

returns a mapping from resource names to the corresponding IP addresses.

Change-Id: Ib9e830e0c54602ac456d64179e1df30f0778906d
Closes-bug: #1356544

commit_message:
Improve Glance profiling

Put osprofiler middleware as a almost first middleware.
This allows us to:
1) Get more preciese duration. We are measuring duration of all middlewares.
2) authenticate middleware is requesting keystone, so if we init osprofiler
   before this middleware, we will get trace infomration from keystone as well.

Change-Id: I11c5d21e6e6b0bd514dee295da410b208d7c798c

commit_message:
Provide the V3 routers to the V3 extension controller

The V3 extension controller needs access to the V3 routers because
they provide the JSON Home data.

bp json-home

Change-Id: Ia455c7c5c06f7cfcefa0bc6afc91bf6954d85e3c

commit_message:
Raise proper exception in case duplicate ipv6 address is allocated

In case neutron tries to generate ipv6 address for slaac subnet,
it doesn't check that generated ip is unique and throws DB exception
that results in 500 HTTP error.

The fix throws proper IpAddressInUse exception.

Closes-Bug: #1358731
Change-Id: I66aed81b8d31d1eff6c87a77c4c4a813179ba458

So this LGTM, but, I don't think this is the fix you needed for that bug. Since by doing this the isolated tenants created for the ceilometer tests here won't be brought up with networking on neutron.

Instead I think you could just add a safe_setup decorator to the teardown class for the failing test file like:

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/tempest/tree/tempest/api/volume/test_volumes_list.py#n57

it might be worth adding that to the ceilometer notification test file too just to play it safe. But that can come in a separate patch, as it's really a separate change.

That being said I think defaulting without networking is fine because the tests here don't really require it.(although this just my assumption based on looking at the code, most of these tests are skipped) If a test does need it in the future you can just override the leaf test class to enable it."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-25 19:11:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Improved coverage for glance.api.*

Added new tests for glance.api.v2.image_data,
glance.api.v2.image_members, glance.api.v2.images,
glance.api.v2.schemas, glance.api.v2.image_tags,
glance.api.cached_images.

Part of blueprint improve-api-unit-tests

Change-Id: I2bd39e12366dd1b185bf60a8cd1d03a162ba5896

have a logical flow with similar things done together.  Also moves the logging

commit_message:
Re-order stack.sh 1: sanity checks

Part 1 of a series

Re-order the setup and check bits in the top portion of stack.sh to
have a logical flow with similar things done together.

No behaviour changes are intended aside from the order of execution.
Any such changes are bugs.

* Do sanity checks that have no configuration needs earlier
* Do supported distro check earlier

Change-Id: I7d15bac199d6c4382d4a4d222784d34f2707da56

commit_message:
Implement ip_lib.device_exists_with_ip_mac

ip_lib.device_exists simply checks that a device is in an
(optional) namespace. This patch adds
ip_lib.device_exists_with_ip_mac, which also verifies that
the device is configured with the given IP and MAC addresses.
The new function is used in functional tests in a patch
further down the dependency chain.

Added functional tests for ip_lib.device_exists,
ip_lib.device_exists_with_ip_mac.

Implements: blueprint l3-high-availability
Change-Id: I1495bcf1f1a88e2eb78df79cccb64121ccf435fb

commit_message:
Make SQL the default backend for Identity & Assignment unit tests.

We have a goal to deprecate the kvs backends for Identity and
Assignment. Before we can do this, we need to ensure our unit
tests are not dependant on them. This patch sets the Identity
backend for unit tests to SQL. Since, by default, the Assignment
backend will pick the same backend type as Identity, this also
means that it will follow suit.

As well as ensuring correct database initialization, this patch
moves a test that was erronously in v2_auth testing to v3. The
test was passing before due to the fact that the kvs assignment
driver does not correctly honor the domain boundary for all
project APIs.

Change-Id: I7b6e753b379a43d09ad8ea077ed6796d1f2e9a26
Partially-Closes: bug 1077282

commit_message:
Back off initial migration to 35

Upgrading from the Havana release to Juno is failing because the
initial Juno migration doesn't include a couple of migrations that
weren't in the initial Havana release but were added afterwards.

This change adds the 036 migration from Havana back in and moves
the initial Juno migration back to 035.

Change-Id: I1045696d66d7a63587aaaf70230a5eaf46e7d65d
Partial-Bug: #1357498

[{'created': '2014-07-27 19:58:33.000000000', 'message': 'JSON Home support

commit_message:
Allow to create a flavor without specifying id

On current v2 API, "create a flavor" API allows a request without
specifying "id" parameter. The API of v3 API, which is source of
v2.1, doesn't allow it now. However, it will cause a backwards
incompatible issue when implementing v2.1 API.
This patch makes v3 API allow it.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Yeah, based on what Jenkins came back with, it looks like there are some tempest tests that rely on certain calls returning 404.
To get this change to merge, you would first need to get a tempest change merged to skip those tests, then get this change merged, then fix the tests to expect a 405.'}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-07-01 21:28:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Chris, do you think such change will have any compatibility impact? Do you know if the glance API has any version support?'}, {'account_id': 9126, 'date': '2014-07-01 21:45:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yes, I think any API change can have a compatibility impact. But I think this falls under the 4th bullet here: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/APIChangeGuidelines#Generally_Considered_OK

For glanceclient specifically, I don't think there would be a problem, since glanceclient wouldn't send requests for resources using an unsupported HTTP method."}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2014-07-02 08:59:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Direction is correct, but the implementation needs bit more logic as 405 is not as straight forward as for example 404.

Please refer to my comment in line.'}, {'account_id': 12114, 'date': '2014-07-03 00:33:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Erno, thanks for the review. After reading your comment, I realized that the current code doesn't behave exactly the way we want. Since it will now return a 405 for all unmatched requests, including ones that should've returned a 404. For example, sending a GET to /v2/nonexistant-resource now returns a 405. Looks like we need more specific return cases for each resource.. but may take much more code"}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2014-07-04 23:20:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I have one thought for the handling logic of 405 http response stuff. You added some mappings and action callback functions to do a patterned logic in v1&2/images.py and router.py, IMO those all functions has very similar logic, and obviously they are a case-by-case approach for different allowed http method combination, so I think if we can reduce those duplicated logic it will be better - less code and easier code reading.

As a suggestion to reduce the duplication, what my idea is to add the common logic for 405 into glance.common.wsgi.APIMapper, there are two ways for implementation:

1. To add a reject() method (or other name you like) and define a controller with a logging and an action functions, which two functions just like what you added in images controller for v1 or v2. For reject() method, we can add a "allowed_methods" keyword parameter, and internally just call routes.Mapper.connect() with the controller and action we new added, then in router.py we can just call reject() directly with a "allowed_methods" list/parameter on those disallowed url, and in that new controller we can just do the log and generate a relevant headers argument for webob.exc.HTTPMethodNotAllowed object.

2. If you think adding new reject() method and adding new controller for logging and action of 405 returning in glance.common.wsgi.APIMapper is not good - they are not common enough for APIMapper class - you like put those stuff in v1&2/images.py controller still, then we can just overwrite connect() method in APIMapper class only, to add  a "allowed_methods" keyword parameter, and internally just call mapper.connect() of routers.Mapper.connect() but set "allowed_methods" list to action function (I mean "fun.allowed_methods = kwargs.pop('allowed_methods', [])"), and finally in v1&2/images.py we just need one common action and a log function.

Both implementation approach could reduce duplicated code/logic from v1&2/images.py but only #1 way could reduce more code for v1&2/router.py, imho reject() call only needs two parameters - url and allowed_methods.

Thoughts?

-1 for geting folks' notice due to there's a +2 and no negative cent.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-08 09:22:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-07-01 18:22:54.000000000', 'message': 'Changes HTTP response code for unsupported HTTP methods

Requests for resources with an unsupported HTTP method now return a HTTP response 405 (Method Not Allowed) rather than a 404 (Not Found).
For example, attempting to DELETE on /v2/images will now return a 405 instead of a 404.

Change-Id: I5406f8ee423d3d5e66c56a26a7009b4f438a7e0f
Closes-Bug: #1297362
'}, {'created': '2014-07-01 18:58:38.000000000', 'message': 'Changes HTTP response code for unsupported methods

Requests for resources with an unsupported HTTP method now return a HTTP
response 405 (Method Not Allowed) rather than a 404 (Not Found). For
example, attempting to DELETE on /v2/images will now return a 405
instead of a 404.

Change-Id: I5406f8ee423d3d5e66c56a26a7009b4f438a7e0f
Closes-Bug: #1297362
'}, {'created': '2014-07-08 00:49:39.000000000', 'message': "Changes HTTP response code for unsupported methods

Requests for resources with an unsupported HTTP method now return a HTTP
response 405 (Method Not Allowed) or 501 (Not Implemented) rather than a
404 (Not Found) for everything.

For example, attempting to DELETE on /v2/images will now return a 405
instead of a 404 and will provide a response header 'Allow' that lists
the valid methods for the resource.

Attempting to use NON_EXISTANT_METHOD on /v2/images will now return a
501.

Attempting to GET on /v2/non_existant_resource will, as expected, return
a 404.

Change-Id: I5406f8ee423d3d5e66c56a26a7009b4f438a7e0f
Closes-Bug: #1297362

commit_message:
Changes HTTP response code for unsupported methods

Requests for resources with an unsupported HTTP method now return a HTTP
response 405 (Method Not Allowed) or 501 (Not Implemented) rather than a
404 (Not Found) for everything.

For example, attempting to DELETE on /v2/images will now return a 405
instead of a 404 and will provide a response header 'Allow' that lists
the valid methods for the resource.

Attempting to use NON_EXISTENT_METHOD on /v2/images will now return a
501.

Attempting to GET on /v2/non_existent_resource will, as expected, return
a 404.

Fixed for v1 and v2.

Change-Id: I5406f8ee423d3d5e66c56a26a7009b4f438a7e0f
Closes-Bug: #1297362

commit_message:
Bump zake up to 0.1

It was about time to release zake 0.1 so this was done after
we added multiple fake client/s -> one fake storage support
and verified that the basics work so we should be good to
use this in projects that want to...

commit_message:
handle invalid seamicro_api_version

If the value for seamicro_api_version is invalid, seamicro raises
an exception. Instead of the seamicro exception, this patch raises
an InvalidParameterValue exception instead.

Change-Id: I2526304e8aedbf2c2822296e3963462ce980d466
Partial-Bug: #1267693

commit_message:
Take iSCSI deploy out of pxe driver

This commit aims at separating the iSCSI deploy portions
from pxe driver so that it can reused in the newly proposed
iLO virtualmedia driver.

Implements: blueprint ironic-ilo-virtualmedia-driver
Change-Id: Id0a4b0fab797c884448a27b1cd5e3a1da05786a7

commit_message:
neutronv2: treat instance as object in deallocate_for_instance

The deallocate_for_instance method is given an instance object
but the neutronv2 API was treating it like a dict. This changes
the method to use dot notatoin for accessing fields on the
object and updates the unit tests to pass an instance object
rather than a dict.

Part of blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: I784d1d59c23da8485d355251aba26b98bd9c7a16

commit_message:
Remove _instance_update usage in _default_block_device_names

We have an instance object in _default_block_device_names so
we can just call instance.save() directly.  We don't need to
update resource tracker stats so there is no need to call
_instance_update in this method.

Part of blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: Ia8faa67a36ff31a3ba526770f5d8a0361326ffc7

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Remove duplicated code in test_user_data

In test_user_data, there is duplicated code for creating a request.
In addition, there is an internal method which works as almost same
as the duplicated code.
This patch makes the tests use the internal method and removes the
duplicated code for cleanup.

Change-Id: Ie87cc14a3ac67bc1262de155dc0a1dcf5c5e7d9a
